man physicians]]\n[[Category:Court physicians]]\n[[Category:Herbalists]]\n[[Category:History of anatomy]]\n[[Category:History of neuroscience]]\n[[Category:People from Pergamon]]\n[[Category:Roman-era Greeks]]\n[[Category:Aelii]]\n[[Category:2nd-century physicians]]\n[[Category:3rd-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Ancient ophthalmologists]]\n", "name_user": "82.25.134.21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed crucial infomation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galen"}
{"title_page": "Shabir Ally", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Overly detailed|date=February 2019}}\n{{Third-party|date=February 2015}}}}\n{{Infobox philosopher <!-- Preacher Category -->\n|region           = \n|color            = \n|image            = Dr._Shabir_Ally.jpg\n|image_size       = \n|caption          = Shabir Ally in 2013\n|name             = Shabir Ally\n|birth_date       = \n|death_date       = \n|education        = [[Laurentian University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[University of Toronto]] {{small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[ Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|school_tradition = \n|main_interests   = [[Dawah]]\n|notable_ideas    = \n|influenced       = \n|signature        = \n|website          = {{url|shabirally.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Shabir Ally''' is a Canadian [[Muslim]] preacher and [[Imam]]. He is the founder of the TV and online show ''Let the Quran Speak''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quranspeaks.com/#|title=QuranSpeaks.com - Home of Let the Quran Speak|website=Quranspeaks.com|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nShabir Ally was born in [[Guyana]] and moved to [[Canada]] with his family in 1978. He gained his B.A. in [[Religious studies|Religious Studies]] from [[Laurentian University]] and his M.A. and Ph.D. from the [[University of Toronto]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalpurplenews.com/22898/carousel/the-new-testament-fact-or-fiction/|title=The New Testament: Fact or Fiction - Royal Purple News|last=Neurock|first=Gabriella|date=2018-04-03|website=Royalpurplenews.com|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> His PhD thesis was on the [[exegesis]] of the [[Quran|Qur'an]] ([[Tafsir]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/35061/1/Ally_Shabir_201211_PhD_thesis.pdf.pdf|format=PDF|author=Shabir Ally|title=The Culmination of Tradition-based Tafs\u012br : The Qur\u02bc\u0101n Exegesis al-Durr al-manth\u016br of al-Suy\u016b\u1e6d\u012b (d. 911/1505)|website=Tspace.library.utoronto.ca|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Reply to [[Robert Morey (pastor)|Robert Morey]]'s source of Islam theories'', Riyadh, Saudi Arabia : Dar Al-Hadyan, 1997.\n*''Is Jesus God? The Bible Says No!'', Riyadh, Saudi Arabia : Dar Al-Hadyan, 1998.\n*''101 questions to ask visiting Jehovah's Witnesses'', Toronto, Canada : Islamic Information & Da\u02bcwah Centre International, 1997. A second volume is entitled ''Another five questions to keep you going''.\n*''Yahweh, Jehovah or Allah : which is God's real name?'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 1999.\n*''101 clear contradictions in the Bible'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 2001.\n*''What God said about eating pork : & issue for Muslims / Christian dialogue'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 2003.\n*''Science in the Qur'an'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 2003.\n*''Common questions people ask about Islam'', Toronto, Canada : Islamic Information & Da`wah Centre International, 2008.\n*''Christianity Vs. Islam : A Muslim and a Christian Debate 8 Crucial Questions'', Minnesota, United States : [[Bethany House Publishers]], 2014. Co-authored with [[James R. White]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.shabirally.com Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ally, Shabir}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Guyanese emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Laurentian University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Muslim apologists]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Gujarati descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Overly detailed|date=February 2019}}\n{{Third-party|date=February 2015}}}}\n{{Infobox philosopher <!-- Preacher Category -->\n|region           = \n|color            = \n|image            = Dr._Shabir_Ally.jpg\n|image_size       = \n|caption          = Shabir Ally in 2013\n|name             = Shabir Ally\n|birth_date       = \n|death_date       = \n|education        = [[Laurentian University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[University of Toronto]] {{small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[ Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|school_tradition = \n|main_interests   = [[Dawah]]\n|notable_ideas    = \n|influenced       = \n|signature        = \n|website          = {{url|shabirally.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Shabir Ally''' is a Canadian [[Muslim]] preacher and the president of the Islamic Information & Dawah Centre International in [[Toronto]] where he functions as an [[Imam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.islaminfo.com/|title=Islaminfo Homepage|website=Islaminfo.com|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref> He is the founder of the TV and online show ''Let the Quran Speak''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quranspeaks.com/#|title=QuranSpeaks.com - Home of Let the Quran Speak|website=Quranspeaks.com|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nShabir Ally was born in [[Guyana]] and moved to [[Canada]] with his family in 1978. He gained his B.A. in [[Religious studies|Religious Studies]] from [[Laurentian University]] and his M.A. and Ph.D. from the [[University of Toronto]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalpurplenews.com/22898/carousel/the-new-testament-fact-or-fiction/|title=The New Testament: Fact or Fiction - Royal Purple News|last=Neurock|first=Gabriella|date=2018-04-03|website=Royalpurplenews.com|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> His PhD thesis was on the [[exegesis]] of the [[Quran|Qur'an]] ([[Tafsir]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/35061/1/Ally_Shabir_201211_PhD_thesis.pdf.pdf|format=PDF|author=Shabir Ally|title=The Culmination of Tradition-based Tafs\u012br : The Qur\u02bc\u0101n Exegesis al-Durr al-manth\u016br of al-Suy\u016b\u1e6d\u012b (d. 911/1505)|website=Tspace.library.utoronto.ca|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Reply to [[Robert Morey (pastor)|Robert Morey]]'s source of Islam theories'', Riyadh, Saudi Arabia : Dar Al-Hadyan, 1997.\n*''Is Jesus God? The Bible Says No!'', Riyadh, Saudi Arabia : Dar Al-Hadyan, 1998.\n*''101 questions to ask visiting Jehovah's Witnesses'', Toronto, Canada : Islamic Information & Da\u02bcwah Centre International, 1997. A second volume is entitled ''Another five questions to keep you going''.\n*''Yahweh, Jehovah or Allah : which is God's real name?'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 1999.\n*''101 clear contradictions in the Bible'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 2001.\n*''What God said about eating pork : & issue for Muslims / Christian dialogue'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 2003.\n*''Science in the Qur'an'', Toronto, Canada : Al-Attique, 2003.\n*''Common questions people ask about Islam'', Toronto, Canada : Islamic Information & Da`wah Centre International, 2008.\n*''Christianity Vs. Islam : A Muslim and a Christian Debate 8 Crucial Questions'', Minnesota, United States : [[Bethany House Publishers]], 2014. Co-authored with [[James R. White]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.shabirally.com Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ally, Shabir}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Guyanese emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Laurentian University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Muslim apologists]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Gujarati descent]]\n", "name_user": "GorgeCustersSabre", "label": "safe", "comment": "This article can't be referenced with pages from the  Islamic Information & Dawah Centre International\u2018s own website. SeeWP:SOURCES", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shabir_Ally"}
{"title_page": "William MacRae", "text_new": "{{for|the Scottish politician|Willie McRae}}\n{{distinguish|William McRae}}\n\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= William MacRae\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1834|9|9}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1882|2|11|1834|9|9}}\n|image= William MacRae.png\n|caption=\n|nickname= \n|birth_place= [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n|death_place= [[Augusta, Georgia]]\n|placeofburial=Oakdale Cemetery<br/>Wilmington, North Carolina\n|allegiance= {{Flag|Confederate States of America}}\n|branch= {{army|CSA}}\n|serviceyears= 1861-1865\n|rank=  [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n|unit=\n|commands=[[J. Johnston Pettigrew|Pettigrew]]-[[William Whedbee Kirkland|Kirkland]]-MacRae [[Brigade]]\n|battles= \n[[American Civil War]]\n*[[Peninsula Campaign]]\n*[[Battle of Second Bull Run|Second Manassas]]\n*[[Maryland Campaign]]\n**[[Battle of Antietam]]\n*[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]\n*[[Battle of Bristoe Station]]\n*[[Overland Campaign]]\n*[[Siege of Petersburg]]\n*[[Appomattox Campaign]]\n|awards=\n|relations=\n|laterwork= Railroad superintendent\n}}\n\n'''William MacRae''' (September 9, 1834 \u2013 February 11, 1882) was a brigadier general in the Confederate States Army during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Early life==\nWilliam MacRae was born September 9, 1834, in Wilmington, NC a son of General Alexander MacRae and Anna Jane Martin MacRae. His family was descended from the [[Clan MacRae|clan MacRae]], of Rosshire, [[Scotland]]. MacRae was educated in [[civil engineering]]. He was working in the profession at [[Monroe, NC]] when the Civil War broke out.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://library.uncw.edu/web/collections/manuscript/MS039.html MS039<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[http://members.aol.com/jweaver303/nc/macrae.htm Brigadier General William MacRae<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Civil War==\nMacRae enlisted as a private in the Monroe light infantry, and was elected [[captain (United States)|captain]] when it became Company B, Fifteenth North Carolina infantry regiment. In April 1862, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]]. During the Peninsula Campaign and at Second Manassas his regiment was a part of [[Howell Cobb]]'s brigade. At the Battle of Antietam, MacRae commanded the brigade which had been reduced to 250 men during the fighting over the previous few weeks. MacRae's brigade repulsed three Union assaults but fell back when he had only 50 effectives remaining and his supply of ammunition was exhausted. At the Fredericksburg he fought with his regiment at Marye's Heights. Immediately following the battle the 15th North Carolina was transferred to Brigadier General [[John Rogers Cooke]]'s North Carolina brigade. Cooke had been badly wounded at Fredericksburg and would not return to the brigade until April 1863. In February 1863, MacRae was promoted to [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]]. This brigade served in North Carolina and southeast Virginia until after the [[Gettysburg Campaign]]. in February, 1863, colonel, and in 1864 was commissioned brigadier-general. After rejoining the [[Army of Northern Virginia]], MacRae was distinguished for valor at the [[Battle of Bristoe Station]]. After Brigadier General [[William Whedbee Kirkland]] was wounded at the [[Battle of Cold Harbor]] MacRae was temporarily promoted to the rank of brigadier general and was assigned to the command of Kirkland's brigade (this was also the former brigade of Brigadier General [[J. Johnston Pettigrew]]). At the [[Second Battle of Ream's Station|Ream's Station]] MacRae's, [[James Henry Lane (Confederate general)|Lane's]], and Cooke's brigades drove [[John Gibbon]]'s 2nd Division of [[Winfield Scott Hancock]]'s [[II Corps (ACW)|II Corps]] from its entrenchments in their front and captured an artillery battery. After meritorious service at the [[Battle of Boydton Plank Road]] MacRae remained with the army through the Appomattox Campaign.<ref name=autogenerated2/><ref name=autogenerated1/><ref>[http://www.aphillcsa.com/macrae.html And Then A.P. Hill Came Up - Biography of William MacRae<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Post War life==\nMacRae returned to North Carolina financially ruined. He became general superintendent of the Wilmington & Manchester Railroad. He took the same position with the [[Macon and Brunswick Railroad]], and finally the [[Western & Atlantic Railroad]].<ref name=autogenerated2/><ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n==Death==\nMacRae contracted [[pneumonia]] and died at Augusta, Georgia. He is buried in his hometown of Wilmington, NC at Oakdale Cemetery.<ref name=autogenerated2/>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War|Biography}}\n*[[List of American Civil War generals (Confederate)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-8047-3641-1}}.\n* Hess, Earl J. ''Lee's Tar Heels: The Pettigrew-Kirkland-MacRae Brigade.'' Chapel Hill, NC: University of North Carolina Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-8078-2687-1}}\n* Sifakis, Stewart. ''Who Was Who in the Civil War.'' New York: Facts On File, 1988. {{ISBN|978-0-8160-1055-4}}.\n* [[Ezra J. Warner (historian)|Warner, Ezra J.]] ''Generals in Gray: Lives of the Confederate Commanders.'' Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press, 1959. {{ISBN|978-0-8071-0823-9}}.\n* http://library.uncw.edu/web/collections/manuscript/MS039.html\n* http://www.aphillcsa.com/macrae.html\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|10050|accessdate=2008-06-27}}\n*[http://library.uncw.edu/web/collections/manuscript/MS039.html UNC Wilmington MacRae papers]\n*[http://www.aphillcsa.com/macrae.html Web biography]\n*[http://members.aol.com/jweaver303/nc/macrae.htm Web biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macrae, William}}\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1882 deaths]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army generals]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army officers]]\n[[Category:People of North Carolina in the American Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Scottish politician|Willie MacRae}}\n{{distinguish|William McRae}}\n\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= William MacRae\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1834|9|9}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1882|2|11|1834|9|9}}\n|image= William MacRae.png\n|caption=\n|nickname= \n|birth_place= [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n|death_place= [[Augusta, Georgia]]\n|placeofburial=Oakdale Cemetery<br/>Wilmington, North Carolina\n|allegiance= {{Flag|Confederate States of America}}\n|branch= {{army|CSA}}\n|serviceyears= 1861-1865\n|rank=  [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n|unit=\n|commands=[[J. Johnston Pettigrew|Pettigrew]]-[[William Whedbee Kirkland|Kirkland]]-MacRae [[Brigade]]\n|battles= \n[[American Civil War]]\n*[[Peninsula Campaign]]\n*[[Battle of Second Bull Run|Second Manassas]]\n*[[Maryland Campaign]]\n**[[Battle of Antietam]]\n*[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]\n*[[Battle of Bristoe Station]]\n*[[Overland Campaign]]\n*[[Siege of Petersburg]]\n*[[Appomattox Campaign]]\n|awards=\n|relations=\n|laterwork= Railroad superintendent\n}}\n\n'''William MacRae''' (September 9, 1834 \u2013 February 11, 1882) was a brigadier general in the Confederate States Army during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Early life==\nWilliam MacRae was born September 9, 1834, in Wilmington, NC a son of General Alexander MacRae and Anna Jane Martin MacRae. His family was descended from the [[Clan MacRae|clan MacRae]], of Rosshire, [[Scotland]]. MacRae was educated in [[civil engineering]]. He was working in the profession at [[Monroe, NC]] when the Civil War broke out.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://library.uncw.edu/web/collections/manuscript/MS039.html MS039<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[http://members.aol.com/jweaver303/nc/macrae.htm Brigadier General William MacRae<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Civil War==\nMacRae enlisted as a private in the Monroe light infantry, and was elected [[captain (United States)|captain]] when it became Company B, Fifteenth North Carolina infantry regiment. In April 1862, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]]. During the Peninsula Campaign and at Second Manassas his regiment was a part of [[Howell Cobb]]'s brigade. At the Battle of Antietam, MacRae commanded the brigade which had been reduced to 250 men during the fighting over the previous few weeks. MacRae's brigade repulsed three Union assaults but fell back when he had only 50 effectives remaining and his supply of ammunition was exhausted. At the Fredericksburg he fought with his regiment at Marye's Heights. Immediately following the battle the 15th North Carolina was transferred to Brigadier General [[John Rogers Cooke]]'s North Carolina brigade. Cooke had been badly wounded at Fredericksburg and would not return to the brigade until April 1863. In February 1863, MacRae was promoted to [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]]. This brigade served in North Carolina and southeast Virginia until after the [[Gettysburg Campaign]]. in February, 1863, colonel, and in 1864 was commissioned brigadier-general. After rejoining the [[Army of Northern Virginia]], MacRae was distinguished for valor at the [[Battle of Bristoe Station]]. After Brigadier General [[William Whedbee Kirkland]] was wounded at the [[Battle of Cold Harbor]] MacRae was temporarily promoted to the rank of brigadier general and was assigned to the command of Kirkland's brigade (this was also the former brigade of Brigadier General [[J. Johnston Pettigrew]]). At the [[Second Battle of Ream's Station|Ream's Station]] MacRae's, [[James Henry Lane (Confederate general)|Lane's]], and Cooke's brigades drove [[John Gibbon]]'s 2nd Division of [[Winfield Scott Hancock]]'s [[II Corps (ACW)|II Corps]] from its entrenchments in their front and captured an artillery battery. After meritorious service at the [[Battle of Boydton Plank Road]] MacRae remained with the army through the Appomattox Campaign.<ref name=autogenerated2/><ref name=autogenerated1/><ref>[http://www.aphillcsa.com/macrae.html And Then A.P. Hill Came Up - Biography of William MacRae<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Post War life==\nMacRae returned to North Carolina financially ruined. He became general superintendent of the Wilmington & Manchester Railroad. He took the same position with the [[Macon and Brunswick Railroad]], and finally the [[Western & Atlantic Railroad]].<ref name=autogenerated2/><ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n==Death==\nMacRae contracted [[pneumonia]] and died at Augusta, Georgia. He is buried in his hometown of Wilmington, NC at Oakdale Cemetery.<ref name=autogenerated2/>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War|Biography}}\n*[[List of American Civil War generals (Confederate)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-8047-3641-1}}.\n* Hess, Earl J. ''Lee's Tar Heels: The Pettigrew-Kirkland-MacRae Brigade.'' Chapel Hill, NC: University of North Carolina Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-8078-2687-1}}\n* Sifakis, Stewart. ''Who Was Who in the Civil War.'' New York: Facts On File, 1988. {{ISBN|978-0-8160-1055-4}}.\n* [[Ezra J. Warner (historian)|Warner, Ezra J.]] ''Generals in Gray: Lives of the Confederate Commanders.'' Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press, 1959. {{ISBN|978-0-8071-0823-9}}.\n* http://library.uncw.edu/web/collections/manuscript/MS039.html\n* http://www.aphillcsa.com/macrae.html\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|10050|accessdate=2008-06-27}}\n*[http://library.uncw.edu/web/collections/manuscript/MS039.html UNC Wilmington MacRae papers]\n*[http://www.aphillcsa.com/macrae.html Web biography]\n*[http://members.aol.com/jweaver303/nc/macrae.htm Web biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macrae, William}}\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1882 deaths]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army generals]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army officers]]\n[[Category:People of North Carolina in the American Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "NSH001", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:avoid redirect in hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_MacRae"}
{"title_page": "Jaggi Vasudev", "text_new": "{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Satguru]].}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Jaggi Vasudev}}\n{{short description|Indian yogi, mythic, and author}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| religion           = \n| name               = Jaggi Vasudev <!--Same as article title-->\n| image              = Sadhguru - February 2019 - 2 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1957|09|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mysore]], [[Karnataka]], India\n| death_date         = \n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Vijaya Kumari (Vijji)|1984}}<ref name=\"family\">{{cite blog|work=[[Isha Foundation]] |url=http://isha.sadhguru.org/man/family-matters/vijji/|title=Family Matters - Sadhguru Speaks About His Family|accessdate=14 February 2018}}</ref>\n| children           = 1\n| honors             = [[Padma Vibhushan]]<br>Indira Gandhi Paryavaran Puraskar\n| organization       = [[Isha Foundation]]\n| notable_works      = {{ubl|Inner Engineering|Dhyanalinga|Rally for Rivers|Linga Bhairavi|Adiyogi: The Source of Yoga|Mystic's Musings|Kaveri Calling}}\n| website            = {{url|isha.sadhguru.org}}\n}}\n'''Jaggi Vasudev'''<ref name=name>{{harvnb|Waghorne|2013|p=297}}; Foreword by Pat MacEnulty in {{harvnb|Simone|Sadhguru|2008|p=10}}</ref> (born 3 September 1957), generally referred to as '''Sadhguru''',<ref name=name/>{{efn|\"Sadhguru\", alternatively spelled \"[[sadguru]]\",<ref name=\"Sanghvi2018\">{{citation|last=Sanghvi|first=Rajesh D|title=Going Beyond My Guru's for Human Welfare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ded_DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|year=2018|publisher=Notion Press|isbn=978-1-64429-901-2|page=30}}</ref> means \"real or true [[guru]]\".<ref>{{citation |last=Cornille |first=Catherine |authorlink=Catherine Cornille |title=The Guru in Indian Catholicism: Ambiguity of Opportunity of Inculturation? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vpGr1OkD9xMC&pg=PA103 |year=1992 |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |isbn=978-0-8028-0566-9 |page=103}}</ref> The term has also been translated as \"senior [[sadhu]]; eminent [[preceptor]].\"<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 2nd| publisher = Swaminarayan Aksharpith| isbn = 81-7526-000-9| last = Shantipriyadas| first = S.| title = Pramukh Swami Maharaj| location = Amdavad| date = 1998| page=307}}</ref>}} is an Indian [[yogi]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/don-t-vote-as-part-of-a-tribe-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev-tells-americans-116101600189_1.html|title=Don't vote as part of a tribe, Jaggi Vasudev tells Americans|last=IANS|date=2016-10-09|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2017-06-30}}</ref> and author.<ref name=most-powerful-indians /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/04/why-i-hate-gurus.html|title=Why I Hate Gurus|last=Rao|first=Mallika|date=2018-04-04|website=[[New York (magazine)]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Vasudev established [[Isha Foundation]], which has been involved in various activities in the field of spirituality, education, and environment. The organisation has been subject to mixed reception.\n\nIn 2017, he was awarded [[Padma Vibhushan]]a by the [[Government of India]] for his services in the field of social services.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life and education===\nBorn in [[Mysore]], [[Karnataka]], [[India]], in a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] speaking family,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isha.sadhguru.org/in/en/wisdom/sadhguru-spot/telugu-tamil-telugu|title=isha foundation - Sadhguru: My mother tongue is Telugu}}</ref> Jaggi Vasudev was the youngest of four children \u2013 two boys and two girls. His mother was a housewife and his father an [[ophthalmologist]] with [[Indian Railways]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Inner Engineering A Yogi's guide to joy|last=Sadhguru|publisher=Spiegel & Grau|year=2016|isbn=9780812997804|location=New York|pages=14\u201321|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to the nature of his father's job, the family moved frequently.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite book |title=Jaggi Vasudev More Than A Life |last=Subramaniam |first=Arundhathi |authorlink= |year=2010 |publisher=[[Penguin Group]] |location= |isbn=978-0-670-08512-5 |page= |pages= |url={{Google books|eRtMQQqlNY8C|page=|keywords=|text=more than a life|plainurl=yes}} |accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref>{{rp|39}}\n\nAfter his schooling at [[Demonstration School, Mysore]] and Mahajana Pre-University College, he graduated from the [[University of Mysore]] with a bachelor's degree in English in 1973.<ref name=\"ieved\">{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/i-have-not-read-the-vedas-or-the-upanishads.-i-confess-i-havent-read-the-gita/282381/0 |title='I have not read the Vedas or the Upanishads. I confess I haven't read the Gita' |date=10 March 2008 |accessdate=7 August 2012 |publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref> Vasudev refused to pursue a post-graduate course, despite parental insistence and instead took to business.<ref name=\"mid\" />\n\n===Spirituality===\nAt the age of 25, on 23 September 1982, Vasudev rode up to the [[Chamundi Hill]] and sat on a rock, where he had a 'spiritual experience'.<ref name=\"mid\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Midnights_with_the_Mystic.html?id=Q5yjIrrK8E4C|title=Midnights with the Mystic|last=Simone|first=Cheryl|publisher=[[Hampton Roads Publishing Company]]|year=2008|isbn=978-1-57174-561-3|location=|page=|pages=|authorlink=|accessdate=}}</ref> Six weeks afterwards, he left his business to his friend and travelled extensively in an effort to gain insight into his mystical experience.<ref name=\"mid\" /> After about a year of meditation and travel, he decided to teach yoga to share his inner experience.<ref name=\"mid\" />\n\nIn 1983, he conducted his first yoga class with seven participants in Mysore. Over time, he began conducting yoga classes across [[Karnataka]] and [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] traveling on his motorcycle, subsisting on the produce of his poultry farm rental and donating the collections received from yoga class participants to a local charity on the last day of the class.<ref name=\"mid\" />\n\n=== Family ===\n[[File:Jaggi Vasudev - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2007.jpg|thumb|Jaggi Vasudev at [[Davos]], [[Switzerland]] in 2007]]\nJaggi Vasudev was married to Vijayakumari (also called Vijji). This was Vijayakumari's second marriage. Prior to marrying Vasudev she worked in a bank. The couple had a daughter called Radhe. Vijaya Kumari died in 1997. At that time her father alleged that Vasudev had murdered her; Vasudev termed  the incident as '[[Mahasamadhi]]' and claimed she had told him about it nine months before her death.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://hindi.theprint.in/opinion/how-much-education-is-required-to-speak-and-talk-on-every-subject-in-the-world/43872/|title=\u0926\u0941\u0928\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0939\u0930 \u0935\u093f\u0937\u092f \u092a\u0930 \u092b\u093e\u0907\u0928\u0932 \u092c\u093e\u0924 \u092c\u094b\u0932\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u093f\u090f \u0915\u093f\u0924\u0928\u0940 \u092a\u0922\u093c\u093e\u0908 \u0915\u0940 \u0906\u0935\u0936\u094d\u092f\u0915\u0924\u093e \u0939\u0948?|last=\u092f\u093e\u0926\u0935|first=\u091c\u094d\u092f\u094b\u0924\u093f|date=|website=The Print|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2019/03/05/congress-it-cell-murder-charge-sadhguru.html|title=Congress IT cell chief rakes up old murder charge against Sadhguru; Isha Foundation dismisses it as 'baseless charge'|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> The police investigation gave him a clean chit.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nVasudev's daughter Radhe Jaggi is a trained [[bharatanatyam]] dancer.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Naidu| first = Jaywant| title = When beauty comes to life| work = Deccan Chronicle| accessdate = 2020-02-27| date = 2017-11-26| url = https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/theatre/261117/when-beauty-comes-to-life.html}}</ref> She married Chennai-based classical vocalist Sandeep Narayan in 2014 at Vasudev's Coimbatore ashram in a ceremony attended by many Indian celebrities.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Sangeetha| first = P| title = Sadhguru's daughter gets married in Kovai| work = The Times of India| accessdate = 2020-02-27| date = 2014-10-24| url = https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Sadhgurus-daughter-gets-married-in-Kovai/articleshow/44924821.cms}}</ref>\n\n=== Books and public engagement ===\nJaggi Vasudev is the author of several books. His ''[[Inner Engineering: A Yogi's Guide to Joy]]''<ref name=\"bstand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/don-t-vote-as-part-of-a-tribe-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev-tells-americans-116101600189_1.html|title=Don't vote as part of a tribe, Jaggi Vasudev tells Americans|website=[[Business Standard]]|publisher=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref> appeared in [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] in the \"Health\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/10/09/health/|title=Health|work=The New York Times}}</ref> \"Religion, Spirituality and Faith\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/10/09/religion-spirituality-and-faith/|title=Religion, Spirituality and Faith|work=The New York Times}}</ref> and \"Advice, How-To & Miscellaneous\" categories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/10/09/advice-how-to-and-miscellaneous|title=New York Times Bestsellers - Advice, How-To <nowiki>&</nowiki> Miscellaneous: New this week INNER ENGINEERING|last=|date=2016-10-09|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Vasudev is also the author of ''Mystic's Musings''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/tantra-between-the-covers/article28584632.ece|title=Tantra between the covers|date=2005-07-15|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and ''Death: An Inside Story''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/spiritual-leader-sadhgurus-new-book-to-demystify-death/1699568|title=Spiritual leader Sadhguru''s new book to demystify death|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/maha-shivratri-2020-vp-venkaiah-naidu-joins-sadhguru-in-celebrations-at-isha-foundation|title=Maha Shivratri 2020: VP Venkaiah Naidu joins Sadhguru in celebrations at Isha Foundation|website=Free Press Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nVasudev is a frequent public speaker who has been invited to address many prestigious forums and conferences across the globe, such as the [[United Nation]]'s Millennium World Peace Summit, the [[House of Lords]], the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], and the [[International Institute for Management Development]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hudson|Hudson|2017|p=2}}</ref> He has also spoken at the annual [[World Economic Forum]]  in 2007,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chandrasekhar |first1=Anand |title=Indian gurus and their Swiss watches: a history |url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/clockwork-orange_indian-gurus-and-their-swiss-watches--a-history/44868044 |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=SWI swissinfo.ch |language=en}}</ref> 2017 and 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/sadhguru-to-deliver-keynote-conduct-meditation-session-at-davos-summit-2465795.html|title=Sadhguru to Deliver Keynote, Conduct Meditation Session at Davos Summit|website=News18|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-sundaymagazine/Golf-with-the-Guru/article15941259.ece|title=Golf with the Guru|date=2009-03-15|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-27|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Honours ===\n[[File:The President, Shri Pranab Mukherjee presenting the Padma Vibhushan Award to Sadhguru Jagadish Vasudev, at the Civil Investiture Ceremony, at Rashtrapati Bhavan, in New Delhi on April 13, 2017.jpg|thumb|[[Pranab Mukherjee]] presenting the [[Padma Vibhushan]] to Vasudev at the [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]] in New Delhi on April 13, 2017]]\nVasudev received the [[Padma Vibhushan]], the second-highest [[civilian award]] from the [[Government of India]] in 2017 in recognition of his contribution to the field of spirituality.<ref name=\"padma\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/Sadhguru-Jaggi-Vasudev-Mariyappan-among-Padma-award-winners/article17095664.ece|title=Jaggi Vasudev, Mariyappan among Padma award winners|date=26 Jan 2017|work=The Hindu|access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/260117/sharad-pawar-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev-awarded-with-padma-vibhushan.html|title=Padma Vibhushan award for Sharad Pawar and Jaggi Vasudev|date=26 January 2017|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref> He stood 92nd in [[The Indian Express]]' list of 100 most powerful Indians, in 2012 and stood 40th in [[India Today]]\u2019s\u00a0list of 50 most powerful Indians, in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/the-most-powerful-indians-in-2012-no.-91100/916140/1|title=The most powerful Indians in 2012: No. 91-100 - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/20190805-top-50-power-people-the-high-mighty-part-4-1573244-2019-07-26|title=Top 50 power people {{!}} The High & Mighty Part-4|last=S|first=MG Arun Shwweta Punj Suhani Singh Kaushik Deka Prachi Bhuchar Chinki Sinha Anshuman Tiwari|last2=July 26|first2=eep Unnithan Amarnath K. Menon Anilesh S. Mahajan Uday Mahurkar|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|last3=August 5|first3=2019 ISSUE DATE:|last4=July 26|first4=2019UPDATED:|last5=Ist|first5=2019 15:35}}</ref>\n\n==Isha Foundation==\n{{Further|Isha Foundation}}\nLocated on the foothills of the [[Velliangiri Mountains]], forty kilometres from the city of [[Coimbatore]] in the state of [[Tamil Nadu]], South India,<ref name=berghella-69>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=69}}</ref> [[Isha Foundation]] was established as a non-profit organisation by Jaggi Vasudev in 1992.<ref name=most-powerful-indians>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/the-most-powerful-indians-in-2009-8084/432810/ |title=The most powerful Indians in 2009: 80\u201384 |date=9 March 2009 |accessdate=22 January 2020 |publisher=[[Indian Express]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128080021/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/the-most-powerful-indians-in-2009-8084/432810/ |archivedate=28 January 2011 }}</ref> Its social initiatives have been awarded with the [[Rashtriya Khel Protsahan Puraskar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/sep/26/rashtriya-khel-protsahan-puraskar-for-isha-outreach-1877222.html|title=Rashtriya Khel Protsahan Puraskar for Isha Outreach|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Yoga ===\n\n====Yoga programmes====\n[[File:Bse class.jpg|thumb|Jaggi Vasudev conducting the Inner Engineering Program at the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]]|alt=]]\nAfter the establishment of the ashram, Vasudev began conducting yoga programmes on the premises of the newly established Isha Yoga Center in 1994, including a course for the [[India men's national field hockey team|Indian Hockey team]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ishafoundation.org/component/option,com_newscomponent/Itemid,885/act,view/id,687/ |title=Morale-Booster says Bhaskaran |date=26 November 1996 |accessdate= |publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Refreshed Team Begins Final Preparation |date=2 December 1996 |url=https://www.ishafoundation.org/component/option,com_newscomponent/Itemid,885/act,view/id,688/|accessdate= |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> In 1997, he began conducting classes in the United States<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303195500/https://www.ishafoundation.org/news/newsclips/nashville1.pdf |title=Yoga guru touts peace, not religion |date=15 October 1997 |accessdate= |work=[[The Tennessean]]| first=Jay|last=Hamburg| pages=1B\u20132B}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= |title=It doesn't take a guru to know which way the stress flows |date=17 March 1998 |accessdate= |publisher=[[Dayton Daily News]]}}</ref> and from 1998 onwards, for [[Life imprisonment|life-term prisoners]] in Tamil Nadu prisons.<ref>{{cite news |url= |title=Yoga Brings 'Freedom' to Prisoners |date=16 February 1998 |accessdate= |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref><ref name=\"SingletonGoldberg2013\">{{cite book|author1=Mark Singleton|author2=Ellen Goldberg|title=Gurus of Modern Yoga|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=walBCgAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|date=6 November 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-993871-1|pages=283 \u2013295}}</ref>\n\nThe flagship program is titled 'Inner Engineering', which introduces people to simple Yoga practices and the ''Shambhavi Mahamudra'';<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report_in-pursuit-of-peace-of-mind_1496488 | title=In pursuit of peace of mind |date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> corporate leadership forms a core audience of these programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://businesstoday.intoday.in/bt/story/3428/1/the-route-to-dharmacracy.html|title=The route to 'dharmacracy'|date=27 November 2008|publisher=[[Business Today (business magazine)|Business Today]]|accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref> It views depression as the result of a false widespread belief about an ability to change the world according to one's desires, and offers to teach the technology of mental well-being, to help one acclimatize with unavoidable work rigors.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Politics_of_Time_and_Youth_in_Brand.html?id=wd2cAQAAQBAJ|title=The Politics of Time and Youth in Brand India: Bargaining with Capital|last=Kapur|first=Jyotsna|date=2013|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-0-85728-109-8|location=|pages=89|chapter=For Some Dreams a Lifetime is Not Enough: The Rasa Aesthetic and the Everyday in Neoliberalism|jstor=j.ctt1gxpc43|chapter-url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/politics-of-time-and-youth-in-brand-india/for-some-dreams-a-lifetime-is-not-enough-the-rasa-aesthetic-and-the-everyday-in-neoliberalism/6CFBCD9273C38DD9D79AE0314E90C71F}}</ref> Vasudev has frequently cited a study by the University of California which supposedly found [[mahamudra]] to lead to highly elevated levels (221%) of neuronal regeneration in the brain; it has since been noted that the study appeared in a fringe journal published by a discredited alternative medicine advocate and his allies, and that it merely reports lower levels of subjective stress from a medium-sized uncontrolled group practicing yoga daily for six weeks.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peterson|first=Christine Tara|last2=Bauer|first2=Sarah M.|last3=Chopra|first3=Deepak|author-link3=Deepak Chopra|last4=Mills|first4=Paul J.|last5=Maturi|first5=Raj K.|date=22 September 2017|title=Effects of Shambhavi Mahamudra Kriya , a Multicomponent Breath-Based Yogic Practice ( Pranayama ), on Perceived Stress and General Well-Being|journal=Journal of Evidence-Based Complementary & Alternative Medicine|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=788\u2013797|doi=10.1177/2156587217730934|issn=2156-5872|pmc=5871312|pmid=29228793}}</ref>\n\n====The Dhyanalinga====\nThe Dhyanalinga (composed of the terms ''[[Dhyana in Hinduism|dhy\u0101na]]'' and ''[[Lingam|linga]]'') is a consecrated sculptural stone structure standing 4.3 metres (13 feet 9 inches) tall.<ref name=berghella-74>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=74}}</ref> Its creation and [[consecration]], according to  Vasudev, was his life's mission entrusted to him by his [[guru]], Palani Swami.<ref name=\"mid\" /> In 1998, the structure of the Dhyanalinga was ordered and arrived at the [[ashram]], where the Dhyanalinga Yogic Temple was being built to hold it.<ref name=berghella-70>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=70}}</ref> After three years of work, the temple was completed on 23 June 1999<ref>{{cite news|url=|title=Dhyanalingam installed|date=26 July 1999|accessdate=|publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref> and opened to the public on 23 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=|title=A multi religious temple|date=19 November 1999|accessdate=|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> As a meditative space the Dhyanalinga Yogic Temple is not dedicated to any particular faith or belief system<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2003/07/25/stories/2003072501630600.htm|title=Transformation of the inner Self|last=Rangaswamy|first=Sudhakshina|date=25 July 2003|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=4 June 2011}}</ref> and is open to all visitors irrespective of their religion or nationality.<ref name=berghella-72>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=72}}</ref>  A stone pillar named the Sarva Dharma [[stambha]], located at the temple's front entrance, has religious symbols of several religions carved on to it to denote universal brotherhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/09/28/stories/13280795.htm|title=Haven for the spiritually inclined|last=Ganapathy|first=T.K.|date=28 September 2001|accessdate=4 June 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127004810/http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/09/28/stories/13280795.htm|archive-date=27 January 2013|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Haven for the Spiritually Inclined - The Hindu - 28 September, 2001 - Isha Foundation |url=http://beta.ishafoundation.org/component/option,com_newscomponent/Itemid,288/act,view/id,670/lang,hi/ |website=beta.ishafoundation.org |publisher=Isha Foundation |accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Adiyogi Shiva statue====\n{{Further|Adiyogi Shiva statue}}\n[[File:IMG j257.jpg|thumb|[[Adiyogi Shiva statue]]|alt=]]\nDesigned by Vasudev, the foundation built a 112-feet-tall and {{Convert|500|t}} [[Adiyogi Shiva statue|Shiva statue]] for inspiring and promoting [[yoga]]. It was inaugurated by the [[Prime Minister of India]], [[Narendra Modi]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-to-unveil-first-112-foot-tall-shiva-statue-in-coimbatore-on-mahashivratri-5-interesting-facts-to-know/563295/|title=PM Narendra Modi unveils first 112-foot tall Shiva statue in Coimbatore|date=24 February 2017|accessdate=1 March 2017|publisher=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]}}</ref> and has been since recognized as the \"Largest Bust Sculpture\" by Guinness World Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/458751-largest-bust-sculpture|title=Largest bust (sculpture)|website=Guinness World Records}}</ref> It is a part of the [[Incredible India]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-maha-shivratri-2017-pm-modi-unveils-112-foot-statue-in-coimbatore-hails-health-benefits-of-yoga-2333914|title=Maha Shivratri 2017: PM Modi unveils 112-foot Shiva statue in Coimbatore|last=Team|first=DNA Web|date=2017-02-24|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu government has since claimed the entire construction as illegal, for which no approval was granted;<ref name=\"TNM_Illegal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/ishas-shiva-statue-has-no-approval-buildings-illegal-tn-government-takes-stand-57938|title=Isha's Shiva statue has no approval, buildings illegal: TN government takes a stand|date=1 March 2017|work=[[The News Minute]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> [[Comptroller and Auditor General of India|Comptroller and Auditor General]]'s report further states the construction to have flagrantly violated the rules of biodiversity zones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/cag-pulls-up-tamil-nadu-forest-department-over-unapproved-construction-by-isha-foundation-in-protected-zone-4718781.html|title=CAG pulls up Tamil Nadu forest department over unapproved construction by Isha Foundation in protected zone|website=Firstpost|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/isha-foundation-flouted-norms-cag/article24393672.ece|title=Isha Foundation flouted norms: CAG|last=Kumar|first=B. Aravind|date=2018-07-12|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/isha-foundation-jaggi-illegal-yoga-centre|title=But Why Is the Cauvery Calling?|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==== Other consecrations ====\nVasudev regularly conducts gatherings (''[[satsang|mahasathsangs]]'') in the Indian states of [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/12/14/stories/2010121450650300.htm |title=Isha's Green Salem goes on stream |date=14 December 2010 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> He also takes spiritual aspirants on annual pilgrimages (''[[yatra]]s'') to [[Mount Kailash]] and the [[Himalayas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newindianexpress.com/nation/article113158.ece |title=Isha shows the way |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report_mansarovar-is-beyond-words_1431882 |title=Mansarovar is beyond words |date=1 September 2010 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref>\n\nEvery year at the Isha Yoga Center, Vasudev celebrates an all-night [[Mahashivarathri]], the annual Hindu festival in honour of [[Shiva]]. It is estimated that these celebrations were attended by as many as 800,000 people in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ishafoundation.org/news/newsclips/2013/Bazaar-15-June-2013.pdf | title=The Lure of Isha | work=[[Harpers Bazaar]] | date=June 2013 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | author=Zakaria, Namrata | pages=106\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/fashion-label-to-yogi-donna-karan-on-an-indian-holiday/1087745/ | title=Fashion label to 'yogi': Donna Karan on an Indian holiday | work=[[The Indian Express]] | date=14 March 2013 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | author=Zakaria, Namrata}}</ref><ref name=\"outlook\">{{cite news | url=http://travel.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?284848 | title=Holy Days | work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] | date=1 April 2013 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | author=Vyas, Sheetal | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927134803/http://travel.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?284848 | archivedate=27 September 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He has also established a Linga Bhairavi temple in Coimbatore where women conduct the rituals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/feb/23/ma-linga-bhairavi-temple-in-coimbatore-allows-only-women-to-perform-pooja-even-during-menstruation-2107376.html|title=Ma Linga Bhairavi temple in Coimbatore allows only women to perform pooja even during menstruation|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Isha Vidhya ===\nIsha Vidhya, an education initiative, aims to raise the level of education and literacy in rural India by providing quality English-language-based, computer-aided education. There are seven Isha Vidhya Schools in operation which educate around 3,000 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hindu.com/2010/04/07/stories/2010040751230200.htm|title=LIC gives grant to Isha|date=7 April 2010|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410101532/http://www.hindu.com/2010/04/07/stories/2010040751230200.htm|archivedate=10 April 2010|accessdate=2 February 2010}}</ref> The foundation also runs an Action for Rural Rejuvenation program, in over 4200 villages, targeting socioeeconomic welfare of underprivileged populace .\n\n=== Environmental initiatives ===\nIt has consultative status with the UN Economic and Social Council,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/paperless/reports/E2010INF4.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and is an accredited observer of the UN Convention to Combat Desertification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://knowledge.unccd.int/cso/isha-foundation|title=Isha Foundation {{!}} Knowledge Hub|website=knowledge.unccd.int|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Narendra Modi, Prime Minister of India, praised the efforts by foundation for carrying forward [[Swachh Bharat Mission]] in Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pm-praises-sadhguru-for-carrying-forward-swachh-bharat-in-tn-118091500572_1.html|title=PM praises Sadhguru for carrying forward Swachh Bharat in TN|date=2018-09-15|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==== Project GreenHands ====\n[[File:PGH_nurseries.jpg|right|thumb|Saplings being readied for transportation at a PGH nursery.]]\nProject GreenHands (PGH) was established in 2004 as an environmental organization. Its activity is largely focused on [[Tamil Nadu]]. The organization received the  Indira Gandhi Paryavaran Puraskar, the [[Government of India]]'s environmental award in 2010.<ref name=\"guin\">[http://www.hindu.com/2010/06/08/stories/2010060850280200.htm Award for Project Green Hands] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521084525/http://www.hindu.com/2010/06/08/stories/2010060850280200.htm|date=2011-05-21}}, ''[[The Hindu]]'', 8 June 2010, retrieved on 8 June 2010</ref> The organisation's activities include [[agroforestry]], plant nurseries in schools,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/feb/07/ishas-green-school-movement-kicks-off-in-kanchi-dist-1769618.html|title=Isha's Green School Movement kicks-off in Kanchi dist|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref> and tree-planting in urban centers such as [[Tiruchirappalli]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Tiruchirapalli/Green-Tiruchi-Movement-seeks-to-rectify-ailing-environment/article15768688.ece|title=Green Tiruchi Movement seeks to rectify ailing environment|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2010-10-04|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and [[Tiruppur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/Stalin-inaugurates-Green-Tirupur-Movement/article16539707.ece|title=Stalin inaugurates Green Tirupur Movement|date=2009-08-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==== Rally for Rivers ====\nThe Rally for Rivers campaign, which ran from September to October 2017,<ref name=\"thirumurthy-tree-planting\">{{Cite news|first= Priyanka | last=Thirumurthy | title= \u2018Why tree planting is not the answer\u2019: Experts question Jaggi\u2019s 'shallow' Rally for Rivers | work= The News Minute |date= 2017-09-06 | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-tree-planting-not-answer-experts-question-jaggi-s-rally-rivers-68004|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> intended to rejuvenate India's depleting rivers by growing large forests along their banks. Promoted by Vasudev all over the country, the campaign received support from a broad range of celebrities and the urban populace.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/rally-for-rivers-isha-foundations-campaign-has-good-intentions-but-minimal-scientific-backing-4022799.html|title=Rally for Rivers: Isha Foundation's campaign has good intentions but minimal scientific backing|website=Firstpost|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> [[Memorandum of understanding|MOU]]<nowiki/>s were signed with state governments.\n\nHowever, the campaign has been widely criticized by environmentalists for lacking in scientific basis and shifting the spotlight away from real concerns.<ref name=\"RfRCrit\">Sources criticizing the program:-\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/rally-for-rivers-isha-foundations-campaign-has-good-intentions-but-minimal-scientific-backing-4022799.html|title=Rally for Rivers: Isha Foundation's campaign has good intentions but minimal scientific backing|website=Firstpost|access-date=2019-12-31}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/rally-for-rivers-jaggi-vasudev-trees-narmada-adani-sand-mining|title=Jaggi Vasudev's 'Rally for Rivers' Will Worsen the Problem It Plans to Tackle|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-12-31}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/forests-wont-do-the-trick-for-rivers/article22417854.ece|title=Forests won't do the trick for rivers|last=Harsha|first=J.|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}\n*{{Cite news|first= Priyanka | last=Thirumurthy | title= \u2018Why tree planting is not the answer\u2019: Experts question Jaggi\u2019s 'shallow' Rally for Rivers | work= The News Minute |date= 2017-09-06 | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-tree-planting-not-answer-experts-question-jaggi-s-rally-rivers-68004|access-date=2020-01-02}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/jaggi-vasudev-rally-for-rivers-isha-foundation-cauvery-riverbank-sand-mining|title=The Empty Environmentalism of 'Rally for Rivers'|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-02}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2018/03/rally-for-rivers-un-world-water-day-spd/|title=How an Indian Guru Aims to Clean the World's Most Polluted Rivers|date=2018-03-21|website=National Geographic News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/energy-and-environment/do-trees-make-rivers-flow/article19853181.ece|title=Do trees make rivers flow?|last=Krishnan|first=Priyanka Runwal and Lalitha|date=2017-10-14|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/asia/indian-guru-s-drive-to-save-rivers-is-timely-but-questionable-1.627150|title=Indian guru's drive to save rivers is timely but questionable|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Acclaimed water conservationist [[Rajendra Singh]] alleges that the campaign is motivated by the goal of money and fame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/862029/jaggi-vasudevs-rivers-campaign-meant-for-fame-power-money-says-indias-waterman-rajendra-singh|title=Jaggi Vasudev's rivers campaign meant for fame, power, money, says India's 'Waterman' Rajendra Singh|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==== Cauvery Calling ====\n{{Further|Cauvery calling}}\n\nThe Cauvery Calling project aims to support farmers in planting an estimated 2.4 billion trees through [[agroforestry]], thereby covering one third of [[Kaveri|Cauvery basin]] with trees, as a means of conserving it. The project has received acclaim from politicians and members of the movie industry.\n\nHowever, environmentalists and public intellectuals allege that the program presents a simplistic view of river conservation, sidesteps social issues, and has the potential to harm tributaries and wildlife habitats.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/cauvery-calling-ngos-urge-leonardo-dicaprio-to-withdraw-support/article29511545.ece|title=Cauvery Calling: NGOs urge Leonardo DiCaprio to withdraw support|date=2019-09-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-07|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/leonardo-dicaprio-cauvery-calling-civil-society-groups|title=Civil Society Groups Ask Leonardo DiCaprio to Revoke Support for 'Cauvery Calling'|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/n-ram-questions-jaggi-vasudevs-cauvery-calling-asks-why-it-shifts-goal-posts-112838|work=The News Minute | title=N Ram questions Jaggi Vasudev's Cauvery Calling, asks why it shifts goal posts|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> A [[Public interest litigation in India|Public Interest litigation]] has also been filed in the Karnataka High Court questioning the legality of the fundraising practices for the initiative, and the usage of government owned land for a private purpose without supporting study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/news-updates/-karnataka-high-court-issues-notice-on-pil-challenging-fund-collection-for-cauvery-calling-project-148186|title=Karnataka High Court Issues Notice On PIL Challenging Fund Collection For 'Cauvery Calling' Project|last=Plumber|first=Mustafa|date=2019-09-18|website=livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/140919/pil-filed-against-cauvery-calling-campaign.html|title=PIL filed against Cauvery Calling campaign|date=2019-09-14|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/sep/18/pil-to-cap-cash-collection-for-cauvery-calling-project-2035326.html|title=PIL to cap cash collection for 'Cauvery Calling' project|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/hc-notice-to-state-on-plea-to-examine-isha-foundations-cauvery-calling-project/article29443669.ece|title=HC notice to State on plea to examine Isha Foundation's 'Cauvery Calling' project|date=2019-09-18|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-07|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> In January 2020, the High Court ruled that the Foundation needed to disclose details of its fundraising practices relating to the initiative.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Disclose details of money collected under \u2018Cauvery Calling\u2019: HC to Isha Foundation| work = The New Indian Express| accessdate = 2020-02-25| date = 2020-01-08| url = https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2020/jan/08/disclose-details-of-money-collected-under-cauvery-calling-hc-2086658.html}}</ref>\n\n== Politics, religion and pseudoscience ==\nCritics note that Vasudev shares the sociopolitical ideology of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and [[Hindutva]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/politics/why-hindutva-nationalists-need-a-sadhguru|title=Why Hindutva Nationalists Need a Sadhguru|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Poruthiyil|first=Prabhir Vishnu|date=2019-08-03|title=Big Business and Fascism: A Dangerous Collusion|journal=Journal of Business Ethics|language=en|doi=10.1007/s10551-019-04259-9|issn=1573-0697}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gopalakrishnan|first=Shankar|date=2006|title=Defining, Constructing and Policing a 'New India': Relationship between Neoliberalism and Hindutva|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2006/26/special-articles/defining-constructing-and-policing-new-india.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=41|issue=26|pages=2803\u20132813|issn=0012-9976|jstor=4418408}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/948963/how-jaggi-vasudev-has-helped-strengthen-fears-about-muslims|title=How Jaggi Vasudev has helped strengthen fears about Muslims|last=Waghmore|first=Qudsiya Contractor & Suryakant|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> He plays a vital role in Indian right-wing politics, using his suave and seemingly apolitical guru persona to spread an exclusionary brand of non-secular ethno-nationalism to an urban audience.<ref name=\":6\"/>\n\nHe advocates a total ban on [[Cattle slaughter in India|cow slaughter]] and deems the [[Islamic rulers in the Indian subcontinent|Muslim Rule in India]] as centuries of \"oppressive occupation\", which were far worse than the [[British Raj]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Vasudev has also spoken in favour of the [[2019 Balakot airstrike]], [[One Hundred and First Amendment of the Constitution of India|introduction of a comprehensive GST]] and [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] whilst deeming the [[Thoothukudi massacre|Thoothukudi protests]] as lynching of corporate industries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/voices/opinion/sadhguru-caa-video-misleading-on-nrc-protesters-gaslighting-attempt|title=Jaggi Vasudev's CAA Video: 22 Minutes of Half-Truths & Gaslighting|date=2019-12-31|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/politics/an-unenlightened-sadhguru-in-king-modis-court|title=An (Un)Enlightened Sadhguru in King Modi's Court|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/948364/watch-jaggi-vasudev-wants-students-to-read-caa-before-protesting-but-hasnt-read-it-himself|title=Watch: Jaggi Vasudev wants students to read CAA before protesting, but hasn't read it himself|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> In an interview before Times Now, Vasudev had blamed the left liberal sections of the society for facilitating militancy in Kashmir and lamented about how [[Kanhaiya Kumar]] and [[Umar Khalid]] (of [[JNU sedition row]] fame) were hogging the public limelight instead of being behind the bars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianage.com/life/more-features/040319/fuelling-peace-with-hatred.html|title=Fuelling peace with hatred|last=Basu|first=Joyeeta|date=2019-03-05|website=The Asian Age|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> His understanding of [[realpolitik]] and history, as displayed in delivering these stances, has been widely criticized.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nVasudev has also been noted as a longstanding purveyor of pseudo-scientific information across a spectrum of topics, aligning to a politico-religious model.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nirmukta.com/2012/07/26/jaggi-vasudev-doesnt-understand-science-or-the-nature-of-the-universe/|title=Jaggi Vasudeva doesn't understand science|last=|first=|date=|website=Nirmukta|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/voices/opinion/sadhguru-indian-mystics-deliver-lectures-top-colleges-india|title=Should Sadhguru be Hosted by India's Top Colleges?|date=2018-09-17|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/927625/opinion-the-disturbing-irrationalism-of-jaggi-vasudev|title=Opinion: The disturbing irrationalism of Jaggi Vasudev|last=Shahane|first=Girish|date=20 June 2019|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he propagated long-debunked superstitions in his blog, about food turning poisonous and human health being adversely affected during [[lunar eclipse]]; the post has been since been broadcast across multiple mainstream media, for years; over a public discourse, he used a [[rudraksha]] garland as an 'energy' measuring device to prove his claim.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/science/yash-pal-pushpa-bhargava-eclipse-jaggi-panchgavya|title=This Is No Way to Remember P.M. Bhargava and Yash Pal|last=Mukunth|first=Vasudevan|date=8 August 2017|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2018/02/03/lunar-eclipse-super-blue-blood-moon-superstition-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev|title=How to spread lunar eclipse superstition using science, Sadhguru explains|last=Sutar|first=Prayas|date=3 February 2018|website=Newslaundry|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> [[AltNews.in|AltNews]] has documented Vasudev to have perpetuated numerous myths around [[Major depressive disorder|clinical depression]]; he had also protested against a potential prohibition on the use of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] for Indian traditional medicines, despite its extreme toxicity which can lead to death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/scientific-research-ascertains-mercury-toxicity-sadhguru-continues-endorse-indian-traditional-medicines/|title=Scientific research ascertains mercury toxicity but Sadhguru continues to endorse it for Indian traditional medicines|last=Shaikh|first=Dr Sumaiya|date=2018-02-26|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/depression-the-myths-falseness-of-sadhgurus-quotes/|title=Depression: The myths & falseness of Sadhguru's quotes|last=Shaikh|first=Dr Sumaiya|date=2018-08-19|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> His views on the [[Higgs boson]] and alleged benefits for the [[Vibhuti]] have been refuted by the rationalists and have been labelled as anti-scientific.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nirmukta.com/2008/11/25/vibhuti-rudraksha-mahatmayam-a-wellness-guide-from-times-of-india/|title=Vibhuti & Rudraksha Mahatmayam: A Wellness Guide from Times of India!|date=2008-11-25|website=Nirmukta|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/ESRnWFGSsiAL7muro7GGmK/Its-a-battle-for-the-survival-of-scientific-research.html|title='It's a battle for the survival of scientific research'|last=Sharma|first=Sanjukta|date=2018-08-18|work=Live Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> In a talk delivered at [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras|IIT Madras]], he propounded debunked theories about [[water memory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arre.co.in/pov/science-spirituality-and-the-psychobabble-of-sadhguru/|title=Science, Spirituality, and the Psychobabble of Sadhguru|date=2018-03-21|website=Arr\u00e9|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Shashi Tharoor]] has noted about how the ideology of [[Hindutva]] has encouraged gurus to blend religion and pseudo-spirituality into a lucrative business to promote irrationality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/features/politics/science-is-not-your-enemy-science-hinduism-1.2653600|title=Science is not your enemy|last=Tharoor|first=Shashi|website=Mathrubhumi|language=en|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> Another piece over [[Scroll.in]], on similar veins, documented Vasudev's casting of religious politics into a meta-scientific narrative and popularization of a Hindutva-centered revisionist history featuring atavistic remembrances of a golden Hindu past; among others it consisted fundamental mis-interpretation of Darwin's work followed by appropriating it as something that has been long discovered in India, advocating for Hindu rituals after death since it spared a slow death (as allegedly justifiable from the continued growth of nail and hairs) and claiming of [[Tantra|Hindu Tantric]] 'scientists' being capable of resurrecting the dead by citing the anecdote.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Babu Gogineni]] deemed of him as a spiritualist conman, who built a huge business empire by resorting to a mixture of pseudo-science with science, rather than old age magic tricks which were increasingly getting debunked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/indias-own-carl-sagan-meet-babu-gogineni-science-populariser-hyderabad-70951|website=thenewsminute.com|access-date=2020-01-02| title=India's own Carl Sagan: Meet Babu Gogineni, the science populariser from Hyderabad}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation| isbn = 978-0-578-20085-9| last = Berghella| first = Vincenzo| title = Chennai and Coimbatore, India| date = 2018}} \n*{{Citation| publisher = SAGE| isbn = 978-1-5264-1437-3| last1 = Hudson| first1 = Simon| last2 = Hudson| first2 = Louise| title = Marketing for Tourism, Hospitality & Events: A Global & Digital Approach| location = London, etc.| date = 2017}}\n* {{citation |last1=Simone |first1=Cheryl |last2=Vasudev |first2=Sadhguru Jaggi |title=Midnights with the Mystic: A Little Guide to Freedom and Bliss |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iWvCxQvsZLgC |year=2008 |publisher=Hampton Roads Publishing |isbn=978-1-61283-113-8}}\n* {{citation |first=Joanne Punzo |last=Waghorne |chapter=Engineering an Artful Practice: On Jaggi Vasudev's Isha Yoga and Sri Sri Ravi Shankar's Art of Living |editor1=Mark Singleton |editor2=Ellen Goldberg |title=Gurus of Modern Yoga |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-cyOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA283 |year=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-993872-8 |pages=283\u2013307}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|voy=no|wikt=no|n=no|species=no|mw=no|m=no|v=no|s=no|b=no}}\n* [http://ishafoundation.org Isha Foundation's official website]\n\n{{Padma Vibhushan Awards}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vasudev, Sadhguru Jaggi}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Hindu mystics]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Indian yogis]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Mysore]]\n[[Category:Spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Vibhushan in other fields]]\n[[Category:Indian environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Advaitin philosophers]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophers]]\n[[Category:Hindu reformers]]\n[[Category:Idealists]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu monks]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Satguru]].}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Jaggi Vasudev}}\n{{short description|Indian yogi, mythic, and author}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| religion           = \n| name               = Jaggi Vasudev <!--Same as article title-->\n| image              = Sadhguru - February 2019 - 2 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1957|09|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mysore]], [[Karnataka]], India\n| death_date         = \n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Vijaya Kumari (Vijji)|1984}}<ref name=\"family\">{{cite blog|work=[[Isha Foundation]] |url=http://isha.sadhguru.org/man/family-matters/vijji/|title=Family Matters - Sadhguru Speaks About His Family|accessdate=14 February 2018}}</ref>\n| children           = 1\n| honors             = [[Padma Vibhushan]]<br>Indira Gandhi Paryavaran Puraskar\n| organization       = [[Isha Foundation]]\n| notable_works      = {{ubl|Inner Engineering|Dhyanalinga|Rally for Rivers|Linga Bhairavi|Adiyogi: The Source of Yoga|Mystic's Musings|Kaveri Calling}}\n| website            = {{url|isha.sadhguru.org}}\n}}\n'''Jaggi Vasudev'''<ref name=name>{{harvnb|Waghorne|2013|p=297}}; Foreword by Pat MacEnulty in {{harvnb|Simone|Sadhguru|2008|p=10}}</ref> (born 3 September 1957), generally referred to as '''Sadhguru''',<ref name=name/>{{efn|\"Sadhguru\", alternatively spelled \"[[sadguru]]\",<ref name=\"Sanghvi2018\">{{citation|last=Sanghvi|first=Rajesh D|title=Going Beyond My Guru's for Human Welfare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ded_DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|year=2018|publisher=Notion Press|isbn=978-1-64429-901-2|page=30}}</ref> means \"real or true [[guru]]\".<ref>{{citation |last=Cornille |first=Catherine |authorlink=Catherine Cornille |title=The Guru in Indian Catholicism: Ambiguity of Opportunity of Inculturation? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vpGr1OkD9xMC&pg=PA103 |year=1992 |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |isbn=978-0-8028-0566-9 |page=103}}</ref> The term has also been translated as \"senior [[sadhu]]; eminent [[preceptor]].\"<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 2nd| publisher = Swaminarayan Aksharpith| isbn = 81-7526-000-9| last = Shantipriyadas| first = S.| title = Pramukh Swami Maharaj| location = Amdavad| date = 1998| page=307}}</ref>}} is an Indian [[yogi]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/don-t-vote-as-part-of-a-tribe-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev-tells-americans-116101600189_1.html|title=Don't vote as part of a tribe, Jaggi Vasudev tells Americans|last=IANS|date=2016-10-09|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2017-06-30}}</ref> and author.<ref name=most-powerful-indians /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/04/why-i-hate-gurus.html|title=Why I Hate Gurus|last=Rao|first=Mallika|date=2018-04-04|website=[[New York (magazine)]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Vasudev established [[Isha Foundation]], which has been involved in various activities in the field of spirituality, education, and environment. The organisation has been subject to mixed reception. \n\nIn 2017, he was awarded [[Padma Vibhushan]]a by the [[Government of India]] for his services in the field of social services.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life and education===\nBorn in [[Mysore]], [[Karnataka]], [[India]], in a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] speaking family,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isha.sadhguru.org/in/en/wisdom/sadhguru-spot/telugu-tamil-telugu|title=isha foundation - Sadhguru: My mother tongue is Telugu}}</ref> Jaggi Vasudev was the youngest of four children \u2013 two boys and two girls. His mother was a housewife and his father an [[ophthalmologist]] with [[Indian Railways]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Inner Engineering A Yogi's guide to joy|last=Sadhguru|publisher=Spiegel & Grau|year=2016|isbn=9780812997804|location=New York|pages=14\u201321|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to the nature of his father's job, the family moved frequently.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite book |title=Jaggi Vasudev More Than A Life |last=Subramaniam |first=Arundhathi |authorlink= |year=2010 |publisher=[[Penguin Group]] |location= |isbn=978-0-670-08512-5 |page= |pages= |url={{Google books|eRtMQQqlNY8C|page=|keywords=|text=more than a life|plainurl=yes}} |accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref>{{rp|39}}\n\nAfter his schooling at [[Demonstration School, Mysore]] and Mahajana Pre-University College, he graduated from the [[University of Mysore]] with a bachelor's degree in English in 1973.<ref name=\"ieved\">{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/i-have-not-read-the-vedas-or-the-upanishads.-i-confess-i-havent-read-the-gita/282381/0 |title='I have not read the Vedas or the Upanishads. I confess I haven't read the Gita' |date=10 March 2008 |accessdate=7 August 2012 |publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref> Vasudev refused to pursue a post-graduate course, despite parental insistence and instead took to business.<ref name=\"mid\" />\n\n===Spirituality===\nAt the age of 25, on 23 September 1982, Vasudev rode up to the [[Chamundi Hill]] and sat on a rock, where he had a 'spiritual experience'.<ref name=\"mid\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Midnights_with_the_Mystic.html?id=Q5yjIrrK8E4C|title=Midnights with the Mystic|last=Simone|first=Cheryl|publisher=[[Hampton Roads Publishing Company]]|year=2008|isbn=978-1-57174-561-3|location=|page=|pages=|authorlink=|accessdate=}}</ref> Six weeks afterwards, he left his business to his friend and travelled extensively in an effort to gain insight into his mystical experience.<ref name=\"mid\" /> After about a year of meditation and travel, he decided to teach yoga to share his inner experience.<ref name=\"mid\" />\n\nIn 1983, he conducted his first yoga class with seven participants in Mysore. Over time, he began conducting yoga classes across [[Karnataka]] and [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] traveling on his motorcycle, subsisting on the produce of his poultry farm rental and donating the collections received from yoga class participants to a local charity on the last day of the class.<ref name=\"mid\" />\n\n=== Family ===\n[[File:Jaggi Vasudev - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2007.jpg|thumb|Jaggi Vasudev at [[Davos]], [[Switzerland]] in 2007]]\nJaggi Vasudev was married to Vijayakumari (also called Vijji). This was Vijayakumari's second marriage. Prior to marrying Vasudev she worked in a bank. The couple had a daughter called Radhe. Vijaya Kumari died in 1997. At that time her father alleged that Vasudev had murdered her; Vasudev termed  the incident as '[[Mahasamadhi]]' and claimed she had told him about it nine months before her death.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://hindi.theprint.in/opinion/how-much-education-is-required-to-speak-and-talk-on-every-subject-in-the-world/43872/|title=\u0926\u0941\u0928\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0939\u0930 \u0935\u093f\u0937\u092f \u092a\u0930 \u092b\u093e\u0907\u0928\u0932 \u092c\u093e\u0924 \u092c\u094b\u0932\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u093f\u090f \u0915\u093f\u0924\u0928\u0940 \u092a\u0922\u093c\u093e\u0908 \u0915\u0940 \u0906\u0935\u0936\u094d\u092f\u0915\u0924\u093e \u0939\u0948?|last=\u092f\u093e\u0926\u0935|first=\u091c\u094d\u092f\u094b\u0924\u093f|date=|website=The Print|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2019/03/05/congress-it-cell-murder-charge-sadhguru.html|title=Congress IT cell chief rakes up old murder charge against Sadhguru; Isha Foundation dismisses it as 'baseless charge'|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> The police investigation gave him a clean chit.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nVasudev's daughter Radhe Jaggi is a trained [[bharatanatyam]] dancer.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Naidu| first = Jaywant| title = When beauty comes to life| work = Deccan Chronicle| accessdate = 2020-02-27| date = 2017-11-26| url = https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/theatre/261117/when-beauty-comes-to-life.html}}</ref> She married Chennai-based classical vocalist Sandeep Narayan in 2014 at Vasudev's Coimbatore ashram in a ceremony attended by many Indian celebrities.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Sangeetha| first = P| title = Sadhguru's daughter gets married in Kovai| work = The Times of India| accessdate = 2020-02-27| date = 2014-10-24| url = https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Sadhgurus-daughter-gets-married-in-Kovai/articleshow/44924821.cms}}</ref>\n\n=== Books and public engagement ===\nJaggi Vasudev is the author of several books. His ''[[Inner Engineering: A Yogi's Guide to Joy]]''<ref name=\"bstand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/don-t-vote-as-part-of-a-tribe-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev-tells-americans-116101600189_1.html|title=Don't vote as part of a tribe, Jaggi Vasudev tells Americans|website=[[Business Standard]]|publisher=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref> appeared in [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] in the \"Health\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/10/09/health/|title=Health|work=The New York Times}}</ref> \"Religion, Spirituality and Faith\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/10/09/religion-spirituality-and-faith/|title=Religion, Spirituality and Faith|work=The New York Times}}</ref> and \"Advice, How-To & Miscellaneous\" categories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/10/09/advice-how-to-and-miscellaneous|title=New York Times Bestsellers - Advice, How-To <nowiki>&</nowiki> Miscellaneous: New this week INNER ENGINEERING|last=|date=2016-10-09|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Vasudev is also the author of ''Mystic's Musings''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/tantra-between-the-covers/article28584632.ece|title=Tantra between the covers|date=2005-07-15|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and ''Death: An Inside Story''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/spiritual-leader-sadhgurus-new-book-to-demystify-death/1699568|title=Spiritual leader Sadhguru''s new book to demystify death|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/maha-shivratri-2020-vp-venkaiah-naidu-joins-sadhguru-in-celebrations-at-isha-foundation|title=Maha Shivratri 2020: VP Venkaiah Naidu joins Sadhguru in celebrations at Isha Foundation|website=Free Press Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nVasudev is a frequent public speaker who has been invited to address many prestigious forums and conferences across the globe, such as the [[United Nation]]'s Millennium World Peace Summit, the [[House of Lords]], the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], and the [[International Institute for Management Development]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hudson|Hudson|2017|p=2}}</ref> He has also spoken at the annual [[World Economic Forum]]  in 2007<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chandrasekhar |first1=Anand |title=Indian gurus and their Swiss watches: a history |url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/clockwork-orange_indian-gurus-and-their-swiss-watches--a-history/44868044 |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=SWI swissinfo.ch |language=en}}</ref>, 2017 and 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/sadhguru-to-deliver-keynote-conduct-meditation-session-at-davos-summit-2465795.html|title=Sadhguru to Deliver Keynote, Conduct Meditation Session at Davos Summit|website=News18|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-sundaymagazine/Golf-with-the-Guru/article15941259.ece|title=Golf with the Guru|date=2009-03-15|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-27|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Honours ===\n[[File:The President, Shri Pranab Mukherjee presenting the Padma Vibhushan Award to Sadhguru Jagadish Vasudev, at the Civil Investiture Ceremony, at Rashtrapati Bhavan, in New Delhi on April 13, 2017.jpg|thumb|[[Pranab Mukherjee]] presenting the [[Padma Vibhushan]] to Vasudev at the [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]] in New Delhi on April 13, 2017]]\nVasudev received the [[Padma Vibhushan]], the second-highest [[civilian award]] from the [[Government of India]] in 2017 in recognition of his contribution to the field of spirituality.<ref name=\"padma\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/Sadhguru-Jaggi-Vasudev-Mariyappan-among-Padma-award-winners/article17095664.ece|title=Jaggi Vasudev, Mariyappan among Padma award winners|date=26 Jan 2017|work=The Hindu|access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/260117/sharad-pawar-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev-awarded-with-padma-vibhushan.html|title=Padma Vibhushan award for Sharad Pawar and Jaggi Vasudev|date=26 January 2017|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref> He stood 92nd in [[The Indian Express]]' list of 100 most powerful Indians, in 2012 and stood 40th in [[India Today]]\u2019s\u00a0list of 50 most powerful Indians, in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/the-most-powerful-indians-in-2012-no.-91100/916140/1|title=The most powerful Indians in 2012: No. 91-100 - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/20190805-top-50-power-people-the-high-mighty-part-4-1573244-2019-07-26|title=Top 50 power people {{!}} The High & Mighty Part-4|last=S|first=MG Arun Shwweta Punj Suhani Singh Kaushik Deka Prachi Bhuchar Chinki Sinha Anshuman Tiwari|last2=July 26|first2=eep Unnithan Amarnath K. Menon Anilesh S. Mahajan Uday Mahurkar|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|last3=August 5|first3=2019 ISSUE DATE:|last4=July 26|first4=2019UPDATED:|last5=Ist|first5=2019 15:35}}</ref>\n\n==Isha Foundation==\n{{Further information|Isha Foundation}}\nLocated on the foothills of the [[Velliangiri Mountains]], forty kilometres from the city of [[Coimbatore]] in the state of [[Tamil Nadu]], South India,<ref name=berghella-69>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=69}}</ref> [[Isha Foundation]] was established as a non-profit organisation by Jaggi Vasudev in 1992.<ref name=most-powerful-indians>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/the-most-powerful-indians-in-2009-8084/432810/ |title=The most powerful Indians in 2009: 80\u201384 |date=9 March 2009 |accessdate=22 January 2020 |publisher=[[Indian Express]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128080021/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/the-most-powerful-indians-in-2009-8084/432810/ |archivedate=28 January 2011 }}</ref> Its social initiatives have been awarded with the [[Rashtriya Khel Protsahan Puraskar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/sep/26/rashtriya-khel-protsahan-puraskar-for-isha-outreach-1877222.html|title=Rashtriya Khel Protsahan Puraskar for Isha Outreach|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> \n\n=== Yoga ===\n\n====Yoga programmes====\n[[File:Bse class.jpg|thumb|Jaggi Vasudev conducting the Inner Engineering Program at the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]]|alt=]]\nAfter the establishment of the ashram, Vasudev began conducting yoga programmes on the premises of the newly established Isha Yoga Center in 1994, including a course for the [[India men's national field hockey team|Indian Hockey team]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ishafoundation.org/component/option,com_newscomponent/Itemid,885/act,view/id,687/ |title=Morale-Booster says Bhaskaran |date=26 November 1996 |accessdate= |publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Refreshed Team Begins Final Preparation |date=2 December 1996 |url=https://www.ishafoundation.org/component/option,com_newscomponent/Itemid,885/act,view/id,688/|accessdate= |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> In 1997, he began conducting classes in the United States<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303195500/https://www.ishafoundation.org/news/newsclips/nashville1.pdf |title=Yoga guru touts peace, not religion |date=15 October 1997 |accessdate= |work=[[The Tennessean]]| first=Jay|last=Hamburg| pages=1B\u20132B}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= |title=It doesn't take a guru to know which way the stress flows |date=17 March 1998 |accessdate= |publisher=[[Dayton Daily News]]}}</ref> and from 1998 onwards, for [[Life imprisonment|life-term prisoners]] in Tamil Nadu prisons.<ref>{{cite news |url= |title=Yoga Brings 'Freedom' to Prisoners |date=16 February 1998 |accessdate= |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> <ref name=\"SingletonGoldberg2013\">{{cite book|author1=Mark Singleton|author2=Ellen Goldberg|title=Gurus of Modern Yoga|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=walBCgAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|date=6 November 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-993871-1|pages=283 \u2013295}}</ref> \n\nThe flagship program is titled 'Inner Engineering', which introduces people to simple Yoga practices and the ''Shambhavi Mahamudra''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report_in-pursuit-of-peace-of-mind_1496488 | title=In pursuit of peace of mind |date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref>; corporate leadership forms a core audience of these programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://businesstoday.intoday.in/bt/story/3428/1/the-route-to-dharmacracy.html|title=The route to 'dharmacracy'|date=27 November 2008|publisher=[[Business Today (business magazine)|Business Today]]|accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref> It views depression as the result of a false widespread belief about an ability to change the world according to one's desires, and offers to teach the technology of mental well-being, to help one acclimatize with unavoidable work rigors.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Politics_of_Time_and_Youth_in_Brand.html?id=wd2cAQAAQBAJ|title=The Politics of Time and Youth in Brand India: Bargaining with Capital|last=Kapur|first=Jyotsna|date=2013|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-0-85728-109-8|location=|pages=89|chapter=For Some Dreams a Lifetime is Not Enough: The Rasa Aesthetic and the Everyday in Neoliberalism|jstor=j.ctt1gxpc43|chapter-url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/politics-of-time-and-youth-in-brand-india/for-some-dreams-a-lifetime-is-not-enough-the-rasa-aesthetic-and-the-everyday-in-neoliberalism/6CFBCD9273C38DD9D79AE0314E90C71F}}</ref> Vasudev has frequently cited a study by the University of California which supposedly found [[mahamudra]] to lead to highly elevated levels (221%) of neuronal regeneration in the brain; it has since been noted that the study appeared in a fringe journal published by a discredited alternative medicine advocate and his allies, and that it merely reports lower levels of subjective stress from a medium-sized uncontrolled group practicing yoga daily for six weeks.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peterson|first=Christine Tara|last2=Bauer|first2=Sarah M.|last3=Chopra|first3=Deepak|author-link3=Deepak Chopra|last4=Mills|first4=Paul J.|last5=Maturi|first5=Raj K.|date=22 September 2017|title=Effects of Shambhavi Mahamudra Kriya , a Multicomponent Breath-Based Yogic Practice ( Pranayama ), on Perceived Stress and General Well-Being|journal=Journal of Evidence-Based Complementary & Alternative Medicine|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=788\u2013797|doi=10.1177/2156587217730934|issn=2156-5872|pmc=5871312|pmid=29228793}}</ref>\n\n====The Dhyanalinga====\nThe Dhyanalinga (composed of the terms ''[[Dhyana_in_Hinduism | dhy\u0101na]]'' and ''[[Lingam|linga]]'') is a consecrated sculptural stone structure standing 4.3 metres (13 feet 9 inches) tall.<ref name=berghella-74>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=74}}</ref> Its creation and [[consecration]], according to  Vasudev, was his life's mission entrusted to him by his [[guru]], Palani Swami.<ref name=\"mid\" /> In 1998, the structure of the Dhyanalinga was ordered and arrived at the [[ashram]], where the Dhyanalinga Yogic Temple was being built to hold it.<ref name=berghella-70>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=70}}</ref> After three years of work, the temple was completed on 23 June 1999<ref>{{cite news|url=|title=Dhyanalingam installed|date=26 July 1999|accessdate=|publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref> and opened to the public on 23 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=|title=A multi religious temple|date=19 November 1999|accessdate=|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> As a meditative space the Dhyanalinga Yogic Temple is not dedicated to any particular faith or belief system<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2003/07/25/stories/2003072501630600.htm|title=Transformation of the inner Self|last=Rangaswamy|first=Sudhakshina|date=25 July 2003|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=4 June 2011}}</ref> and is open to all visitors irrespective of their religion or nationality.<ref name=berghella-72>{{harvnb|Berghella|2018|p=72}}</ref>  A stone pillar named the Sarva Dharma [[stambha]], located at the temple's front entrance, has religious symbols of several religions carved on to it to denote universal brotherhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/09/28/stories/13280795.htm|title=Haven for the spiritually inclined|last=Ganapathy|first=T.K.|date=28 September 2001|accessdate=4 June 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127004810/http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/09/28/stories/13280795.htm|archive-date=27 January 2013|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Haven for the Spiritually Inclined - The Hindu - 28 September, 2001 - Isha Foundation |url=http://beta.ishafoundation.org/component/option,com_newscomponent/Itemid,288/act,view/id,670/lang,hi/ |website=beta.ishafoundation.org |publisher=Isha Foundation |accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Adiyogi Shiva statue====\n{{Further information|Adiyogi Shiva statue}}\n[[File:IMG j257.jpg|thumb|[[Adiyogi Shiva statue]]|alt=]]\nDesigned by Vasudev, the foundation built a 112-feet-tall and {{Convert|500|t}} [[Adiyogi Shiva statue|Shiva statue]] for inspiring and promoting [[yoga]]. It was inaugurated by the [[Prime Minister of India]], [[Narendra Modi]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-to-unveil-first-112-foot-tall-shiva-statue-in-coimbatore-on-mahashivratri-5-interesting-facts-to-know/563295/|title=PM Narendra Modi unveils first 112-foot tall Shiva statue in Coimbatore|date=24 February 2017|accessdate=1 March 2017|publisher=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]}}</ref> and has been since recognized as the \"Largest Bust Sculpture\" by Guinness World Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/458751-largest-bust-sculpture|title=Largest bust (sculpture)|website=Guinness World Records}}</ref> It is a part of the [[Incredible India]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-maha-shivratri-2017-pm-modi-unveils-112-foot-statue-in-coimbatore-hails-health-benefits-of-yoga-2333914|title=Maha Shivratri 2017: PM Modi unveils 112-foot Shiva statue in Coimbatore|last=Team|first=DNA Web|date=2017-02-24|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu government has since claimed the entire construction as illegal, for which no approval was granted;<ref name=\"TNM_Illegal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/ishas-shiva-statue-has-no-approval-buildings-illegal-tn-government-takes-stand-57938|title=Isha's Shiva statue has no approval, buildings illegal: TN government takes a stand|date=1 March 2017|work=[[The News Minute]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> [[Comptroller and Auditor General of India|Comptroller and Auditor General]]'s report further states the construction to have flagrantly violated the rules of biodiversity zones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/cag-pulls-up-tamil-nadu-forest-department-over-unapproved-construction-by-isha-foundation-in-protected-zone-4718781.html|title=CAG pulls up Tamil Nadu forest department over unapproved construction by Isha Foundation in protected zone|website=Firstpost|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/isha-foundation-flouted-norms-cag/article24393672.ece|title=Isha Foundation flouted norms: CAG|last=Kumar|first=B. Aravind|date=2018-07-12|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/isha-foundation-jaggi-illegal-yoga-centre|title=But Why Is the Cauvery Calling?|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==== Other consecrations ====\nVasudev regularly conducts gatherings (''[[satsang|mahasathsangs]]'') in the Indian states of [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/12/14/stories/2010121450650300.htm |title=Isha's Green Salem goes on stream |date=14 December 2010 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> He also takes spiritual aspirants on annual pilgrimages (''[[yatra]]s'') to [[Mount Kailash]] and the [[Himalayas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newindianexpress.com/nation/article113158.ece |title=Isha shows the way |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[Indian Express]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report_mansarovar-is-beyond-words_1431882 |title=Mansarovar is beyond words |date=1 September 2010 |accessdate=25 January 2011 |publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref>\n\nEvery year at the Isha Yoga Center, Vasudev celebrates an all-night [[Mahashivarathri]], the annual Hindu festival in honour of [[Shiva]]. It is estimated that these celebrations were attended by as many as 800,000 people in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ishafoundation.org/news/newsclips/2013/Bazaar-15-June-2013.pdf | title=The Lure of Isha | work=[[Harpers Bazaar]] | date=June 2013 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | author=Zakaria, Namrata | pages=106\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/fashion-label-to-yogi-donna-karan-on-an-indian-holiday/1087745/ | title=Fashion label to 'yogi': Donna Karan on an Indian holiday | work=[[The Indian Express]] | date=14 March 2013 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | author=Zakaria, Namrata}}</ref><ref name=\"outlook\">{{cite news | url=http://travel.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?284848 | title=Holy Days | work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] | date=1 April 2013 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | author=Vyas, Sheetal | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927134803/http://travel.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?284848 | archivedate=27 September 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He has also established a Linga Bhairavi temple in Coimbatore where women conduct the rituals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/feb/23/ma-linga-bhairavi-temple-in-coimbatore-allows-only-women-to-perform-pooja-even-during-menstruation-2107376.html|title=Ma Linga Bhairavi temple in Coimbatore allows only women to perform pooja even during menstruation|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Isha Vidhya ===\nIsha Vidhya, an education initiative, aims to raise the level of education and literacy in rural India by providing quality English-language-based, computer-aided education. There are seven Isha Vidhya Schools in operation which educate around 3,000 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hindu.com/2010/04/07/stories/2010040751230200.htm|title=LIC gives grant to Isha|date=7 April 2010|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410101532/http://www.hindu.com/2010/04/07/stories/2010040751230200.htm|archivedate=10 April 2010|accessdate=2 February 2010}}</ref> The foundation also runs an Action for Rural Rejuvenation program, in over 4200 villages, targeting socioeeconomic welfare of underprivileged populace .\n\n=== Environmental initiatives ===\nIt has consultative status with the UN Economic and Social Council<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/paperless/reports/E2010INF4.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, and is an accredited observer of the UN Convention to Combat Desertification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://knowledge.unccd.int/cso/isha-foundation|title=Isha Foundation {{!}} Knowledge Hub|website=knowledge.unccd.int|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Narendra Modi, Prime Minister of India, praised the efforts by foundation for carrying forward [[Swachh Bharat Mission]] in Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pm-praises-sadhguru-for-carrying-forward-swachh-bharat-in-tn-118091500572_1.html|title=PM praises Sadhguru for carrying forward Swachh Bharat in TN|date=2018-09-15|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> \n\n==== Project GreenHands ====\n[[File:PGH_nurseries.jpg|right|thumb|Saplings being readied for transportation at a PGH nursery.]]\nProject GreenHands (PGH) was established in 2004 as an environmental organization. Its activity is largely focused on [[Tamil Nadu]]. The organization received the  Indira Gandhi Paryavaran Puraskar, the [[Government of India]]'s environmental award in 2010.<ref name=\"guin\">[http://www.hindu.com/2010/06/08/stories/2010060850280200.htm Award for Project Green Hands] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521084525/http://www.hindu.com/2010/06/08/stories/2010060850280200.htm|date=2011-05-21}}, ''[[The Hindu]]'', 8 June 2010, retrieved on 8 June 2010</ref> The organisation's activities include [[agroforestry]], plant nurseries in schools,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/feb/07/ishas-green-school-movement-kicks-off-in-kanchi-dist-1769618.html|title=Isha's Green School Movement kicks-off in Kanchi dist|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref> and tree-planting in urban centers such as [[Tiruchirappalli]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Tiruchirapalli/Green-Tiruchi-Movement-seeks-to-rectify-ailing-environment/article15768688.ece|title=Green Tiruchi Movement seeks to rectify ailing environment|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2010-10-04|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and [[Tiruppur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/Stalin-inaugurates-Green-Tirupur-Movement/article16539707.ece|title=Stalin inaugurates Green Tirupur Movement|date=2009-08-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==== Rally for Rivers ====\nThe Rally for Rivers campaign, which ran from September to October 2017,<ref name=\"thirumurthy-tree-planting\">{{Cite news|first= Priyanka | last=Thirumurthy | title= \u2018Why tree planting is not the answer\u2019: Experts question Jaggi\u2019s 'shallow' Rally for Rivers | work= The News Minute |date= 2017-09-06 | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-tree-planting-not-answer-experts-question-jaggi-s-rally-rivers-68004|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> intended to rejuvenate India's depleting rivers by growing large forests along their banks. Promoted by Vasudev all over the country, the campaign received support from a broad range of celebrities and the urban populace.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/rally-for-rivers-isha-foundations-campaign-has-good-intentions-but-minimal-scientific-backing-4022799.html|title=Rally for Rivers: Isha Foundation's campaign has good intentions but minimal scientific backing|website=Firstpost|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> [[Memorandum of understanding|MOU]]<nowiki/>s were signed with state governments.\n\nHowever, the campaign has been widely criticized by environmentalists for lacking in scientific basis and shifting the spotlight away from real concerns.<ref name=\"RfRCrit\"> Sources criticizing the program:-\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/rally-for-rivers-isha-foundations-campaign-has-good-intentions-but-minimal-scientific-backing-4022799.html|title=Rally for Rivers: Isha Foundation's campaign has good intentions but minimal scientific backing|website=Firstpost|access-date=2019-12-31}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/rally-for-rivers-jaggi-vasudev-trees-narmada-adani-sand-mining|title=Jaggi Vasudev's 'Rally for Rivers' Will Worsen the Problem It Plans to Tackle|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-12-31}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/forests-wont-do-the-trick-for-rivers/article22417854.ece|title=Forests won't do the trick for rivers|last=Harsha|first=J.|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}\n*{{Cite news|first= Priyanka | last=Thirumurthy | title= \u2018Why tree planting is not the answer\u2019: Experts question Jaggi\u2019s 'shallow' Rally for Rivers | work= The News Minute |date= 2017-09-06 | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-tree-planting-not-answer-experts-question-jaggi-s-rally-rivers-68004|access-date=2020-01-02}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/jaggi-vasudev-rally-for-rivers-isha-foundation-cauvery-riverbank-sand-mining|title=The Empty Environmentalism of 'Rally for Rivers'|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-02}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2018/03/rally-for-rivers-un-world-water-day-spd/|title=How an Indian Guru Aims to Clean the World's Most Polluted Rivers|date=2018-03-21|website=National Geographic News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/energy-and-environment/do-trees-make-rivers-flow/article19853181.ece|title=Do trees make rivers flow?|last=Krishnan|first=Priyanka Runwal and Lalitha|date=2017-10-14|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/asia/indian-guru-s-drive-to-save-rivers-is-timely-but-questionable-1.627150|title=Indian guru's drive to save rivers is timely but questionable|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Acclaimed water conservationist [[Rajendra Singh]] alleges that the campaign is motivated by the goal of money and fame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/862029/jaggi-vasudevs-rivers-campaign-meant-for-fame-power-money-says-indias-waterman-rajendra-singh|title=Jaggi Vasudev's rivers campaign meant for fame, power, money, says India's 'Waterman' Rajendra Singh|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> \n\n==== Cauvery Calling ====\n{{Further information|Cauvery calling}}\n\nThe Cauvery Calling project aims to support farmers in planting an estimated 2.4 billion trees through [[agroforestry]], thereby covering one third of [[Kaveri|Cauvery basin]] with trees, as a means of conserving it. The project has received acclaim from politicians and members of the movie industry. \n\nHowever, environmentalists and public intellectuals allege that the program presents a simplistic view of river conservation, sidesteps social issues, and has the potential to harm tributaries and wildlife habitats.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/cauvery-calling-ngos-urge-leonardo-dicaprio-to-withdraw-support/article29511545.ece|title=Cauvery Calling: NGOs urge Leonardo DiCaprio to withdraw support|date=2019-09-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-07|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/leonardo-dicaprio-cauvery-calling-civil-society-groups|title=Civil Society Groups Ask Leonardo DiCaprio to Revoke Support for 'Cauvery Calling'|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/n-ram-questions-jaggi-vasudevs-cauvery-calling-asks-why-it-shifts-goal-posts-112838|work=The News Minute | title=N Ram questions Jaggi Vasudev's Cauvery Calling, asks why it shifts goal posts|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> A [[Public interest litigation in India|Public Interest litigation]] has also been filed in the Karnataka High Court questioning the legality of the fundraising practices for the initiative, and the usage of government owned land for a private purpose without supporting study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/news-updates/-karnataka-high-court-issues-notice-on-pil-challenging-fund-collection-for-cauvery-calling-project-148186|title=Karnataka High Court Issues Notice On PIL Challenging Fund Collection For 'Cauvery Calling' Project|last=Plumber|first=Mustafa|date=2019-09-18|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/140919/pil-filed-against-cauvery-calling-campaign.html|title=PIL filed against Cauvery Calling campaign|date=2019-09-14|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/sep/18/pil-to-cap-cash-collection-for-cauvery-calling-project-2035326.html|title=PIL to cap cash collection for 'Cauvery Calling' project|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/hc-notice-to-state-on-plea-to-examine-isha-foundations-cauvery-calling-project/article29443669.ece|title=HC notice to State on plea to examine Isha Foundation's 'Cauvery Calling' project|date=2019-09-18|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-07|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> In January 2020, the High Court ruled that the Foundation needed to disclose details of its fundraising practices relating to the initiative.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Disclose details of money collected under \u2018Cauvery Calling\u2019: HC to Isha Foundation| work = The New Indian Express| accessdate = 2020-02-25| date = 2020-01-08| url = https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2020/jan/08/disclose-details-of-money-collected-under-cauvery-calling-hc-2086658.html}}</ref>\n\n== Politics, religion and pseudoscience ==\nCritics note that Vasudev shares the sociopolitical ideology of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and [[Hindutva]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/politics/why-hindutva-nationalists-need-a-sadhguru|title=Why Hindutva Nationalists Need a Sadhguru|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Poruthiyil|first=Prabhir Vishnu|date=2019-08-03|title=Big Business and Fascism: A Dangerous Collusion|journal=Journal of Business Ethics|language=en|doi=10.1007/s10551-019-04259-9|issn=1573-0697}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gopalakrishnan|first=Shankar|date=2006|title=Defining, Constructing and Policing a 'New India': Relationship between Neoliberalism and Hindutva|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2006/26/special-articles/defining-constructing-and-policing-new-india.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=41|issue=26|pages=2803\u20132813|issn=0012-9976|jstor=4418408}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/948963/how-jaggi-vasudev-has-helped-strengthen-fears-about-muslims|title=How Jaggi Vasudev has helped strengthen fears about Muslims|last=Waghmore|first=Qudsiya Contractor & Suryakant|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> He plays a vital role in Indian right-wing politics, using his suave and seemingly apolitical guru persona to spread an exclusionary brand of non-secular ethno-nationalism to an urban audience.<ref name=\":6\"/>\n\nHe advocates a total ban on [[Cattle slaughter in India|cow slaughter]] and deems the [[Islamic rulers in the Indian subcontinent|Muslim Rule in India]] as centuries of \"oppressive occupation\", which were far worse than the [[British Raj]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Vasudev has also spoken in favour of the [[2019 Balakot airstrike]], [[One Hundred and First Amendment of the Constitution of India|introduction of a comprehensive GST]] and [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] whilst deeming the [[Thoothukudi massacre|Thoothukudi protests]] as lynching of corporate industries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/voices/opinion/sadhguru-caa-video-misleading-on-nrc-protesters-gaslighting-attempt|title=Jaggi Vasudev's CAA Video: 22 Minutes of Half-Truths & Gaslighting|date=2019-12-31|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/politics/an-unenlightened-sadhguru-in-king-modis-court|title=An (Un)Enlightened Sadhguru in King Modi's Court|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/948364/watch-jaggi-vasudev-wants-students-to-read-caa-before-protesting-but-hasnt-read-it-himself|title=Watch: Jaggi Vasudev wants students to read CAA before protesting, but hasn't read it himself|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> In an interview before Times Now, Vasudev had blamed the left liberal sections of the society for facilitating militancy in Kashmir and lamented about how [[Kanhaiya Kumar]] and [[Umar Khalid]] (of [[JNU sedition row]] fame) were hogging the public limelight instead of being behind the bars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianage.com/life/more-features/040319/fuelling-peace-with-hatred.html|title=Fuelling peace with hatred|last=Basu|first=Joyeeta|date=2019-03-05|website=The Asian Age|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> His understanding of [[realpolitik]] and history, as displayed in delivering these stances, has been widely criticized.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nVasudev has also been noted as a longstanding purveyor of pseudo-scientific information across a spectrum of topics, aligning to a politico-religious model.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nirmukta.com/2012/07/26/jaggi-vasudev-doesnt-understand-science-or-the-nature-of-the-universe/|title=Jaggi Vasudeva doesn't understand science|last=|first=|date=|website=Nirmukta|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/voices/opinion/sadhguru-indian-mystics-deliver-lectures-top-colleges-india|title=Should Sadhguru be Hosted by India's Top Colleges?|date=2018-09-17|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/927625/opinion-the-disturbing-irrationalism-of-jaggi-vasudev|title=Opinion: The disturbing irrationalism of Jaggi Vasudev|last=Shahane|first=Girish|date=20 June 2019|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he propagated long-debunked superstitions in his blog, about food turning poisonous and human health being adversely affected during [[lunar eclipse]]; the post has been since been broadcast across multiple mainstream media, for years; over a public discourse, he used a [[rudraksha]] garland as an 'energy' measuring device to prove his claim.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/science/yash-pal-pushpa-bhargava-eclipse-jaggi-panchgavya|title=This Is No Way to Remember P.M. Bhargava and Yash Pal|last=Mukunth|first=Vasudevan|date=8 August 2017|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2018/02/03/lunar-eclipse-super-blue-blood-moon-superstition-sadhguru-jaggi-vasudev|title=How to spread lunar eclipse superstition using science, Sadhguru explains|last=Sutar|first=Prayas|date=3 February 2018|website=Newslaundry|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> [[AltNews.in|AltNews]] has documented Vasudev to have perpetuated numerous myths around [[Major depressive disorder|clinical depression]]; he had also protested against a potential prohibition on the use of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] for Indian traditional medicines, despite its extreme toxicity which can lead to death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/scientific-research-ascertains-mercury-toxicity-sadhguru-continues-endorse-indian-traditional-medicines/|title=Scientific research ascertains mercury toxicity but Sadhguru continues to endorse it for Indian traditional medicines|last=Shaikh|first=Dr Sumaiya|date=2018-02-26|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/depression-the-myths-falseness-of-sadhgurus-quotes/|title=Depression: The myths & falseness of Sadhguru's quotes|last=Shaikh|first=Dr Sumaiya|date=2018-08-19|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> His views on the [[Higgs boson]] and alleged benefits for the [[Vibhuti]] have been refuted by the rationalists and have been labelled as anti-scientific.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nirmukta.com/2008/11/25/vibhuti-rudraksha-mahatmayam-a-wellness-guide-from-times-of-india/|title=Vibhuti & Rudraksha Mahatmayam: A Wellness Guide from Times of India!|date=2008-11-25|website=Nirmukta|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/ESRnWFGSsiAL7muro7GGmK/Its-a-battle-for-the-survival-of-scientific-research.html|title='It's a battle for the survival of scientific research'|last=Sharma|first=Sanjukta|date=2018-08-18|work=Live Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> In a talk delivered at [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras|IIT Madras]], he propounded debunked theories about [[water memory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arre.co.in/pov/science-spirituality-and-the-psychobabble-of-sadhguru/|title=Science, Spirituality, and the Psychobabble of Sadhguru|date=2018-03-21|website=Arr\u00e9|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Shashi Tharoor]] has noted about how the ideology of [[Hindutva]] has encouraged gurus to blend religion and pseudo-spirituality into a lucrative business to promote irrationality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/features/politics/science-is-not-your-enemy-science-hinduism-1.2653600|title=Science is not your enemy|last=Tharoor|first=Shashi|website=Mathrubhumi|language=en|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> Another piece over [[Scroll.in]], on similar veins, documented Vasudev's casting of religious politics into a meta-scientific narrative and popularization of a Hindutva-centered revisionist history featuring atavistic remembrances of a golden Hindu past; among others it consisted fundamental mis-interpretation of Darwin's work followed by appropriating it as something that has been long discovered in India, advocating for Hindu rituals after death since it spared a slow death (as allegedly justifiable from the continued growth of nail and hairs) and claiming of [[Tantra|Hindu Tantric]] 'scientists' being capable of resurrecting the dead by citing the anecdote.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Babu Gogineni]] deemed of him as a spiritualist conman, who built a huge business empire by resorting to a mixture of pseudo-science with science, rather than old age magic tricks which were increasingly getting debunked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/indias-own-carl-sagan-meet-babu-gogineni-science-populariser-hyderabad-70951|website=thenewsminute.com|access-date=2020-01-02| title=India's own Carl Sagan: Meet Babu Gogineni, the science populariser from Hyderabad}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation| isbn = 978-0-578-20085-9| last = Berghella| first = Vincenzo| title = Chennai and Coimbatore, India| date = 2018}} \n*{{Citation| publisher = SAGE| isbn = 978-1-5264-1437-3| last1 = Hudson| first1 = Simon| last2 = Hudson| first2 = Louise| title = Marketing for Tourism, Hospitality & Events: A Global & Digital Approach| location = London, etc.| date = 2017}}\n* {{citation |last1=Simone |first1=Cheryl |last2=Vasudev |first2=Sadhguru Jaggi |title=Midnights with the Mystic: A Little Guide to Freedom and Bliss |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iWvCxQvsZLgC |year=2008 |publisher=Hampton Roads Publishing |isbn=978-1-61283-113-8}}\n* {{citation |first=Joanne Punzo |last=Waghorne |chapter=Engineering an Artful Practice: On Jaggi Vasudev's Isha Yoga and Sri Sri Ravi Shankar's Art of Living |editor1=Mark Singleton |editor2=Ellen Goldberg |title=Gurus of Modern Yoga |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-cyOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA283 |year=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-993872-8 |pages=283\u2013307}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|voy=no|wikt=no|n=no|species=no|mw=no|m=no|v=no|s=no|b=no}}\n* [http://ishafoundation.org Isha Foundation's official website]\n\n{{Padma Vibhushan Awards}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vasudev, Sadhguru Jaggi}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Hindu mystics]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Indian yogis]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Mysore]]\n[[Category:Spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]