| [[2004 NBA playoffs|2004]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2003\u201304 New York Knicks season|New York]]\n| 1 || 1 || 22.0 || .400 || .000 || .800 || 5.0 || '''3.0''' || .0 || .0 || 12.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2006 NBA playoffs|2006]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2005\u201306 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| '''20''' || '''14''' || '''31.8''' || .491 || .444 || .776 || '''6.3''' || 1.3 || '''.9''' || .4 || 15.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2009 NBA playoffs|2009]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2008\u201309 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 2 || 0 || 7.5 || .300 || .250 || .000 || 1.5 || .0 || .0 || .0 || 3.5\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 55 || 23 || 28.1 || .468 || .436 || .772 || 5.1 || 1.4 || .6 || .5 || 13.3\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\nNBA CAREER STATS = https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/t/thomati01.html\n\nSPORTS ILLUSTRATED STORY 11/15/96 - One Year and Then? https://vault.si.com/vault/1996/11/15/one-year-and-then-villanova-phenom-tim-thomas-gives-it-the-old-college-try-but-the-call-of-the-nba-is-never-out-of-earshot\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/tim_thomas/index.html?nav=page NBA.com profile]\n*[http://www.basketballreference.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=THOMATI01 Stats at BasketballReference]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061115023105/http://clippers.topbuzz.com/modules/gallery/tim-thomas Tim Thomas Pictures & Photos]\n\n{{1997 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Tim}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bulls players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Clippers players]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Bucks players]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Nets draft picks]]\n[[Category:New York Knicks players]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers players]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Suns players]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paterson, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Villanova Wildcats men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player (born 1977)}}\n{{Lead too short|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Tim Thomas\n| image        = Tim Thomas.jpg\n| caption      = Thomas with the Chicago Bulls in 2009\n| team         = \n| number       = \n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 10\n| weight_lb    = 240\n| position     = [[Small forward]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1977|2|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Paterson, New Jersey]]\n| high_school  = [[Paterson Catholic High School|Paterson Catholic]]<br>(Paterson, New Jersey)\n| college      = [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]] (1996\u20131997)\n| draft_year   = 1997\n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 7\n| draft_team   = [[New Jersey Nets]]\n| career_start = 1998\n| career_end   = 2010\n| years1       = {{nbay|1997|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1998|end}}\n| team1        = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| years2       = {{nbay|1998|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2003|end}}\n| team2        = [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| years3       = {{nbay|2003|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2004|end}}\n| team3        = [[New York Knicks]]\n| years4       = {{nbay|2005|full=y}}\n| team4        = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years5       = {{nbay|2005|end}}\n| team5        = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years6       = {{nbay|2006|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|start}}\n| team6        = [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| years7       = {{nbay|2008|full=y}}\n| team7        = New York Knicks\n| years8       = {{nbay|2008|end}}\n| team8        = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years9       = {{nbay|2009|full=y}}\n| team9        = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label   = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value   = 9,454 (11.5 ppg)\n| stat2label   = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value   = 3,379 (4.1 rpg)\n| stat3label   = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value   = 1,272 (1.5 apg)\n| highlights   = \n* [[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]] ({{nbay|1997|end}})\n* ''SN'' Freshman of the Year (1997)\n* Third-team All-[[Big East Conference|Big East]] (1997)\n* All-Big East Tournament Team (1997)\n* [[Big East Conference Men's Basketball Freshman of the Year|Big East Freshman of the Year]] (1997)\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[1996 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|1996]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1995, 1996)\n* Second-team ''Parade'' All-American (1994)\n| bbr          = thomati01\n| profile      = tim_thomas\n}}\n'''Timothy Mark Thomas''' (born February 26, 1977) is a former American professional basketball player. A national sensation in high school and outstanding collegian at Villanova University, the athletic 6'10\" 240lb talent played in the [[National_Basketball_Association|National Basketball Association]] (NBA) from 1998 to 2010 building a 12-year career as a pro between 7 different NBA teams. <ref>https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/t/thomati01.html\n</ref>\n\n==High School==\nA versatile 6'10\" forward with a soft shooting touch, Thomas was tabbed as a future NBA star when he was still in high school, and was selected to the [[McDonald's All-American]] team after averaging 25.3 points and 14.5 rebounds per game as a senior at [[Paterson Catholic High School]]. He was ranked as the #2 recruit in the nation behind only [[Kobe Bryant]] whom almost joined him at Villanova after the two both played in the 1996 High School McDonald's All-American game and the All-Star [[Roundball Classic|Magic Johnson Roundball Classic]] game which they dominated together.  Thomas also seriously considered making the jump straight to the NBA from high school, waiting to declare his decision to attend college at Villanova until just days before the deadline to enter the NBA Draft. <ref>https://vault.si.com/vault/1996/11/15/one-year-and-then-villanova-phenom-tim-thomas-gives-it-the-old-college-try-but-the-call-of-the-nba-is-never-out-of-earshot</ref>\n\n==NCAA career==\nThomas made his mark in his one season in college at Villanova University. Joining a future NBA talent-laden team with [[Alvin Williams#Basketball career|Alvin Williams]], Jason Lawson, John Celestand and Malik Allen, he filled the void of former Big East Player of the Year [[Kerry Kittles#Career highlights|Kerry Kittles]] from the year before and helped lead the Wildcats to a BIG EAST Regular Season Championship under coach Steve Lappas.  Villanova would place 2nd in the Big East tournament but Thomas would be named to both ALL-BIG EAST and ALL-BIG EAST Tournament teams as well as win BIG EAST ROOKIE OF THE YEAR while sporting a 17PPG and 6Reb avg.  Villanova would make the NCAA Tourney but lose in round 2 to a U of California team that featured future NFL All-Pro, [[Tony Gonzalez]].\n\n==NBA career==\nFollowing his freshman year at [[Villanova Wildcats basketball|Villanova University]], he was drafted seventh overall by the [[New Jersey Nets]] in the [[1997 NBA draft]] and was immediately traded to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in exchange for the Sixers' draft pick ([[Keith Van Horn]]).\n\n===Philadelphia 76ers===\nThomas enjoyed a solid rookie season, averaging 11.0 points per game, and was named to the NBA's ALL-ROOKIE 2nd Team. The Sixers would grow impatient with a [[sophomore slump]] from Thomas, though, and in 1999 he and [[Scott Williams (basketball)|Scott Williams]] were traded to the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] for [[Jerald Honeycutt]] and [[Tyrone Hill]].\n\n===Milwaukee Bucks===\nMilwaukee was enamored with Thomas's raw talent and versatility, and hoped he could blossom into a star with more seasoning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2002/10/28/8118866/6-milwaukee-bucks-with-glenn-robinson-gone-tim-thomas-has-a-chance-to-prove-that-hes-worth-his-big-contractand-that-he-can-fetch-more-wins-than-big-dog|title=6 Milwaukee Bucks With Glenn Robinson gone, Tim Thomas has a chance to prove that he's worth his big contract--and that he can fetch more wins than Big Dog|last=Burns|first=Marty|website=Vault|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> It looked like things were coming together for Thomas during the [[2000\u201301 NBA season|2000\u201301 season]], when he averaged a career-high 13.4 ppg for the Bucks. On January 5, 2001, Thomas connected on eight three-point field goals in the second half of Milwaukee's 119\u2013115 loss to [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland]]. During his time with the Bucks, then-teammate [[Ray Allen]] was quoted as saying, \"If he wanted to, Tim Thomas could be the best player in the league.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/feb/21/sports/sp-simers21 | work=Los Angeles Times | title=There is no doubting Thomas will fill a void | date=February 21, 2007}}</ref> Nevertheless, after a strong playoff performance that year, Thomas signed a new deal with the Bucks worth roughly $66 million over six years, despite being offered more money by Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-07-25-0007250353-story.html|title=THOMAS LATEST TO SNUB BULLS|last=Writer|first=Fred Mitchell, Tribune Staff|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n\n===New York Knicks===\nOn February 16, 2004, Thomas was traded to the [[New York Knicks]] in a three-team trade that also included the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/news/story?id=1735956|title=Knicks deal Van Horn in 3-team trade|date=2004-02-15|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> The trade also sent Keith Van Horn, whom Thomas was also traded for during the [[1997 NBA draft|1997 draft]], from the Knicks to the Bucks, [[Nazr Mohammed]] from the Hawks to the Knicks, [[Joel Przybilla]] from the Bucks to the Hawks, and [[Michael Doleac]] from the Knicks to the Hawks.\n\nDuring game 1 of the Knicks' [[2004 NBA playoffs|first-round playoff]] series against the Nets, Thomas suffered an injury that kept him out of the remainder of the playoffs, when he was fouled by [[Jason Collins]] and taken out of the game on a stretcher.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/playoffs2004/news/story?id=1787142 Thomas: K-Mart's act is phony]. Sports.espn.go.com (April 22, 2004). Retrieved on 2012-06-03.</ref> The incident started a long feud with Nets forward [[Kenyon Martin]], who Thomas called a fake tough guy, that continued past both players' playing careers.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/playoffs2004/news/story?id=1787615 K-Mart: Thomas' words mean nothing]. Sports.espn.go.com (April 22, 2004). Retrieved on 2012-06-03.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Thomas rehashed their feud on an episode of the Scoop B Radio Podcast. Thomas told [[Brandon Scoop B Robinson]] that he'd like to settle his feud with [[Kenyon Martin]] once and for all with a boxing match. The proceeds would go to the charity of their choice. Martin declined.<ref>{{Cite web|title =Kenyon Martin Responds To 50 Cent, Tim Thomas Boxing Challenge|url=http://respect-mag.com/2017/01/kenyon-martin-responds-50-cents-boxing-challenge-tim-thomas/|website =[[RESPECT Magazine]]|access-date = May 14, 2018|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Bulls===\nPrior to the 2005\u201306 season, Thomas was traded to the [[Chicago Bulls]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/04/sports/basketball/bulls-curry-is-traded-to-knicks.html|title=Bulls' Curry Is Traded to Knicks|last=Beck|first=Howard|date=2005-10-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> along with [[Jermaine Jackson (basketball)|Jermaine Jackson]], [[Michael Sweetney|Mike Sweetney]], a [[LaMarcus Aldridge|2006 1st-round draft pick]], a [[Joakim Noah|2007 1st-round draft pick]], a [[Kyrylo Fesenko|2007 2nd-round draft pick]] and a [[Jon Brockman|2009 2nd-round draft pick]], in exchange for [[Eddy Curry]], [[Antonio Davis]] and a [[Wilson Chandler|2007 1st-round draft pick]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbatrades.tumblr.com/post/60703134767/new-york-knicks-acquire-eddy-curry-in-five-player|title=New York Knicks Acquire Eddy Curry In Five-Player... - NBA Trades|website=nbatrades.tumblr.com|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n\nPlaying in the final year of his contract, Thomas was given minimal minutes from the rebuilding Bulls. After playing just three games for Chicago, Thomas was deactivated while dealing with ankle<ref name=\"CT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/|title=Chicago Sports News, Schedules & Scores - Chicago Tribune|website=www.chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> and back injuries.<ref name=\"CT\"/> After not playing for nearly four months, Thomas was granted his release from the Bulls.<ref>http://www.suntimes.com/output/bulls/cst-spt-bullnt012.html</ref>\n\n===Phoenix Suns===\nOn March 1, 2006, Thomas agreed to terms with the [[Phoenix Suns]] to a contract for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/jrsuns/jrsuns_thomasgym_vist060318.html|title=Suns Acquire Free Agent Tim Thomas}}</ref> He made his debut with the Suns two days later, scoring 20 points off the bench in a 123\u2013118 win over Orlando.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/game?gameId=260303021|title=Magic vs. Suns - Game Summary - March 3, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> Playing alongside reigning [[NBA MVP]] [[Steve Nash]] (who won a consecutive MVP award that year), Thomas rejuvenated his career in Phoenix.\n\nIn the [[2006 NBA playoffs|playoffs]], Thomas played a crucial role in the Suns run to the Western Conference Finals. Starting in place of injured All-Star [[Amar'e Stoudemire]] (who did not play the entirety of the playoffs), Thomas scored a game-high 22 points with 15 rebounds in a game 1 victory in the first round over the Lakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=260423021|title=Lakers vs. Suns - Box Score - April 23, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> In game 6, Thomas hit the game-tying three at the end of regulation and an important three-pointer late in overtime to seal the Suns' win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=260504013|title=Suns vs. Lakers - Game Recap - May 4, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The Suns won game 7, overcoming a 3\u20131 series deficit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Phoenix Clinches Series Over Lakers|url=http://www.nba.com/playoffs2006/series_phxlal.html|publisher=NBA}}</ref>\n\nIn the Suns' second-round series against the Clippers, Thomas was credited for his defense on [[Elton Brand]],<ref>https://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/0514sunsfeat0514.html</ref> helping the team to another seven-game series win. In the Western Conference Finals, Phoenix fell to the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in six games. In game five of that series, Thomas \"blew a kiss\" to Maverick [[Dirk Nowitzki]], who then proceeded to score a total of 50 points for the game. Thomas expressed an interest in re-signing with Phoenix,<ref>https://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/0627suns0627.html</ref> though the Suns were over the salary cap and expected Stoudemire to return as their starter.<ref>https://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/0630suns0630.html</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Clippers===\nOn July 13, 2006, Thomas signed a four-year, $24 million contract with the [[Los Angeles Clippers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/news/story?id=2518352|title=Tim Thomas joining Clippers|date=2006-07-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> He frequently started in place of [[Elton Brand]] and [[Chris Kaman]], though Thomas himself also battled injuries.\n\n===Second stint with New York===\nOn November 21, 2008, Thomas and [[Cuttino Mobley]] were traded to the New York Knicks, in exchange for [[Zach Randolph]] and [[Mardy Collins]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/2008/news/features/11/21/aldridge.reax/|title=NBA.com: Knicks not done dealing, pull off trade with Clippers|website=www.nba.com|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> In his return to the Knicks, Thomas was reunited with [[Mike D'Antoni]], who was his coach in Phoenix.\n\n===Second stint with Chicago===\nOn February 19, 2009, Thomas was traded again to the Bulls along with center [[Jerome James]] and guard [[Anthony Roberson]] in exchange for guard [[Larry Hughes]] just before the trade deadline.<ref name=\"Thomas back to Bulls\">{{cite web\n|url = http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3919012\n|title = Sources: Knicks trade for Bulls' Hughes\n|first =\n|last = \n|accessdate = February 19, 2009}}</ref> His second stint in Chicago was more successful than his first, as he provided veteran leadership to the young team, helping the Bulls make a late-season push to qualify for the playoffs. Though entering the playoffs as the seventh seed, they were able to push their first-round series against the defending-champion Boston Celtics to a full seven games.\n\nOn July 14, 2009, the Bulls negotiated a buyout of Thomas's $6.5 million contract.<ref>[http://blogs.chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/fullcourtpress/2009/07/bulls-buy-out-thomas.html Bulls buy out Thomas?]</ref>\n\n===Dallas Mavericks===\nOn July 28, 2009, the [[Dallas Mavericks]] signed free agent Thomas. In late January, however, he left the team temporarily to take care of his wife, who had an undisclosed illness.\n\nIn August 2010 Thomas agreed to a one-year deal with the Mavericks worth the veteran minimum. In September of that year, however, he told the club that he would not report to the team so that he could care for his sick wife.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/dallas/nba/news/story?id=5573456&campaign=rss&source=NBAHeadlines Tim Thomas won't play for Mavericks]. Sports.espn.go.com (September 15, 2010). Retrieved on 2012-06-03.</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*Thomas was on the NBA All-Rookie 2nd Team in [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398 season]].\n*He won the ''[[Sporting News]]'' [[Freshman]] of the Year during the [[1996\u201397 NBA season|1996\u201397 season]].\n* Was named to both the 1997 All-Big East and All-Big East Tournament Teams.\n* Won 1997 Big East Freshman of the Year Award\n* Was three-time All American at [[Paterson Catholic High School]] in [[Paterson, New Jersey]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B05EFD81E39F935A35751C1A963958260 \" HIGH SCHOOL BASKETBALL;Top Schoolboy Prospect Pressed About the Pros\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 6, 1995. Accessed December 3, 2007.</ref>\n\n== NBA career statistics ==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n=== Regular season ===\n\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1997}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1997\u201398 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia]]\n| 77 || 48 || 23.1 || .447 || .363 || .740 || 3.7 || 1.2 || .7 || .2 || 11.0\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia]]\n| 17 || 0 || 11.1 || .403 || .263 || .792 || 1.9 || .9 || .2 || .2 || 4.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 Milwaukee Bucks season|Milwaukee]]\n| 33 || 26 || 18.9 || '''.495''' || .327 || .614 || 2.8 || .9 || .7 || .3 || 8.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1999}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1999\u20132000 Milwaukee Bucks season|Milwaukee]]\n| '''80''' || 1 || 26.2 || .461 || .346 || .774 || 4.2 || 1.4 || .7 || .4 || 11.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2000}}\n| style=\"text-align:left