winning broadcasts]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Beyonc\u00e9]]\n", "name_user": "Longdashes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing:column", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemonade_(Beyonc%C3%A9_album)"}
{"title_page": "Raymond Van Gestel", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Raymond Van Gestel\n|image          = Raymond_Van_Gestel.jpg\n|image_size     = 200\n|caption        = Van Gestel in 1953.\n|fullname       =\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|1930|1|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]], Belgium\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|2020|4|17|1930|1|20|df=y}}\n|death_place    = [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]], Belgium\n|height         =\n|position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Right winger]]\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    =\n|years1         = 1946\u20131948\n|clubs1         = [[SV Mol]]\n|caps1          =\n|goals1         =\n|years2         = 1948\u20131958\n|clubs2         = [[K. Lyra|Lyra]]\n|caps2          = 168\n|goals2         = 92\n|years3         = 1958\u20131962\n|clubs3         = [[K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel|Verbroedering Geel]]\n|caps3          =\n|goals3         =\n|totalcaps      = 168+\n|totalgoals     = 92+\n|nationalyears1 = 1951\u20131953\n|nationalteam1  = [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 5\n|nationalgoals1 = 2\n}}\n'''Raymond Van Gestel''' (20 January 1930 - 17 April 2020) was a Belgian [[association football|footballer]], athlete and [[Aircraft pilot|pilot]].<ref name=\"lyralierse\">[https://lyralierse.be/nieuws/mon-van-gestel-overleden/ Mon Van Gestel overleden] lyralierse.be, 19 April 2020, source in Dutch</ref> He spent most of his career with [[K. Lyra|Lyra]].<ref name=\"hln3\">[https://www.hln.be/sport/voetbal/rode-duivels/voormalig-rode-duivel-en-luchtvaarticoon-mon-van-gestel-sterft-op-90-jarige-leeftijd~a32dc6b2/ Voormalig Rode Duivel en luchtvaarticoon Mon Van Gestel sterft op 90-jarige leeftijd] hln.be, 19 April 2020, article in Dutch</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]], Van Gestel played as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]] for [[SV Mol]], [[K. Lyra|Lyra]] and [[K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel|Verbroedering Geel]].<ref name = \"NFT\">{{NFT player|pid=25872|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> In total he played 57 games in the [[Belgian First Division A|first division]] scoring a total of 32 goals.<ref>[http://users.skynet.be/fb304341/ Belgiumsoccerhistory (Peter Mari\u00ebn), website in Dutch]</ref>\n\nIn 1954, when Lyra were promoted to the First Division, he suffered a severe knee injury, largely ending his career.<ref name=\"hoeishetmet\"/> In total he played 168 league games for Lyra, scoring 92 goals.<ref name = \"NFT\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Broes |first1=Hugo |last2=Mari\u00ebn |first2=Peter |title=Kon. Lyra TSV 100 Plus {{!}} De Slegte |date=2016 |pages=294 |edition=1 |url=https://www.deslegte.be/kon-lyra-tsv-100-plus-1616378/ |language=nl-BE}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDuring his career he also earned 5 caps for the [[Belgium national football team|Belgian national team]] between 1951 and 1953, scoring 2 goals.<ref name = \"NFT\"/> Both goals came against Spain on 10 June 1951; the first goal was scored after only 17 seconds in the game, giving him the then-record of the fastest goal scored for the national team.<ref>[https://lyralierse.be/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/LYRALIERSE_magazine_NR1.pdf Nog meer straffe internationals] lyralierse.be, K. Lyra-Lierse Clubmagazine, blz. 21, article in Dutch</ref><ref name=\"lyralierse\"/> Following the game against Spain he was nicknamed ''Raimundo el rapido'' and he was close to a transfer to Spanish club [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]], but Lyra refused the deal.<ref>[https://sporza.be/nl/2020/04/19/rode-duivel-die-na-17-seconden-tegen-spanje-scoort-is-niet-meer~1587331282847/ Rode Duivel die na 17 seconden tegen Spanje scoort, is niet meer] sporza.be, 19 April 2020, article in Dutch</ref>\n\nIn 1954 he was selected for the Belgian squad for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in Z\u00fcrich, but he could not join the team due to a military mission in Africa as a fighter pilot with the [[Belgian Air Component|Belgian air force]].<ref name=\"hoeishetmet\">[https://www.rtv.be/artikels/hoe-het-met-mon-van-gestel-a55976 Hie is het met? Mon Van Gestel] rtv.be, 24 juni 2018, article in Dutch</ref>\n\n==Athletics career==\nHe was also active as an athlete in [[Track and field|the long jump and sprints]]. He was the Belgian [[long jump]] champion.<ref name=\"onderox\">[http://www.onderox.be/nieuws/539/mon-van-gestel-held-op-het-sportveld-en-in-het-luchtruim Mon Van Gestel: held op het sportveld en in het luchtruim] onderox.be, Jef Aerts, article in Dutch</ref> Due to his versatility he is one of the few Belgian athletes ever to compete in different sports at an international level in the same year.<ref name=\"hln2\"/>\n\n==Later life and death==\nVan Gestel was a [[Fighter pilot]] for the Belgian air force and flight instructor.<ref name=\"motorvliegen\">[https://www.motorvliegen.be/files/fly-in-magazine-2018.pdf Keiheuvel fly-in 2018] motorvliegen.be, 2018, blz. 6</ref><ref>[https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/ggv109kic Vlieginstructeur analyseert dodelijke crash] nieuwsblad.be, 16 augustus 2006</ref> As an instructor he trained around 2000 students.<ref>[https://www.rtv.be/artikels/luchtvaarticoon-en-ex-rode-duivel-mon-van-gestel-90-overleden-a81641 Luchtvaarticoon en ex-Rode Duivel Mon Van Gestel (90) overleden] rtv.be, 18 April 2020</ref> Together with his brother he was also one of the founding members of the Belgian [[Flying club]] Keiheuvel.<ref name=\"hln2\">[https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/balen/gewezen-rode-duivel-en-mede-oprichter-van-vliegclub-keiheuvel-mon-van-gestel-90-overleden-zijn-veelzijdigheid-was-indrukwekkend~adc7b8f5/ Gewezen Rode Duivel en mede-oprichter van vliegclub Keiheuvel Mon Van Gestel (90) overleden: \u201cZijn veelzijdigheid was indrukwekkend] hln.be, Wouter Demuynck, 19 April 2020, article in Dutch</ref><ref name=\"gva\">[https://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20200419_04927290/ex-rode-duivel-en-bezieler-aeroclub-keiheuvel-overleden Ex-Rode Duivel en bezieler Aeroclub Keiheuvel overleden] gva.be, mto, 19 April 2020, article in dutch</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]] on 17 April 2020, aged 90.<ref name=\"gva\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Gestel, Raymond}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgium international footballers]]\n[[Category:K. Lyra players]]\n[[Category:K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Belgian Second Division/Belgian First Division B players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Raymond Van Gestel\n|image          = Raymond_Van_Gestel.jpg\n|image_size     = 200\n|caption        = Van Gestel in 1953.\n|fullname       =\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|1930|1|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]], Belgium\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|2020|4|17|1930|1|20|df=y}}\n|death_place    = [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]], Belgium\n|height         =\n|position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Right winger]]\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    =\n|years1         = 1946\u20131948\n|clubs1         = [[SV Mol]]\n|caps1          =\n|goals1         =\n|years2         = 1948\u20131958\n|clubs2         = [[K. Lyra|Lyra]]\n|caps2          = 168\n|goals2         = 92\n|years3         = 1958\u20131962\n|clubs3         = [[K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel|Verbroedering Geel]]\n|caps3          =\n|goals3         =\n|totalcaps      = 168+\n|totalgoals     = 92+\n|nationalyears1 = 1951\u20131953\n|nationalteam1  = [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 5\n|nationalgoals1 = 2\n}}\n'''Raymond Van Gestel''' (20 January 1930 - 17 April 2020) was a Belgian [[association football|footballer]], athlete and [[Aircraft pilot|pilot]].<ref name=\"lyralierse\">[https://lyralierse.be/nieuws/mon-van-gestel-overleden/ Mon Van Gestel overleden] lyralierse.be, 19 April 2020, source in Dutch</ref> He spent most of his career with [[K. Lyra|Lyra]].<ref name=\"hln3\">[https://www.hln.be/sport/voetbal/rode-duivels/voormalig-rode-duivel-en-luchtvaarticoon-mon-van-gestel-sterft-op-90-jarige-leeftijd~a32dc6b2/ Voormalig Rode Duivel en luchtvaarticoon Mon Van Gestel sterft op 90-jarige leeftijd] hln.be, 19 April 2020, article in Dutch</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]], Van Gestel played as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]] for [[SV Mol]], [[K. Lyra|Lyra]] and [[K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel|Verbroedering Geel]].<ref name = \"NFT\">{{NFT player|pid=25872|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> In total he played 57 games in the [[Belgian First Division A|first division]] scoring a total of 32 goals.<ref>[http://users.skynet.be/fb304341/ Belgiumsoccerhistory (Peter Mari\u00ebn), website in Dutch]</ref>\n\nIn 1954, when Lyra were promoted to the First Division, he suffered a severe knee injury, largely ending his career.<ref name=\"hoeishetmet\"/> In total he played 168 league games for Lyra, scoring 92 goals.<ref name = \"NFT\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Broes |first1=Hugo |last2=Mari\u00ebn |first2=Peter |title=Kon. Lyra TSV 100 Plus {{!}} De Slegte |date=2016 |pages=294 |edition=1 |url=https://www.deslegte.be/kon-lyra-tsv-100-plus-1616378/ |language=nl-BE}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDuring his career he also earned 5 caps for the [[Belgium national football team|Belgian national team]] between 1951 and 1953, scoring 2 goals.<ref name = \"NFT\"/> Both goals came against Spain on 10 June 1951; the first goal was scored after only 17 seconds in the game, giving him the then-record of the fastest goal scored for the national team.<ref>[https://lyralierse.be/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/LYRALIERSE_magazine_NR1.pdf Nog meer straffe internationals] lyralierse.be, K. Lyra-Lierse Clubmagazine, blz. 21, article in Dutch</ref><ref name=\"lyralierse\"/> Following the game against Spain he was nicknamed ''Raimundo el rapido'' and he was close to a transfer to Spanish club [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]], but Lyra refused the deal.<ref>[https://sporza.be/nl/2020/04/19/rode-duivel-die-na-17-seconden-tegen-spanje-scoort-is-niet-meer~1587331282847/ Rode Duivel die na 17 seconden tegen Spanje scoort, is niet meer] sporza.be, 19 April 2020, article in Dutch</ref>\n\nIn 1954 he was selected for the Belgian squad for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in Z\u00fcrich, but he could not join the team due to a military mission in Africa as a fighter pilot with the [[Belgian Air Component|Belgian air force]].<ref name=\"hoeishetmet\">[https://www.rtv.be/artikels/hoe-het-met-mon-van-gestel-a55976 Hie is het met? Mon Van Gestel] rtv.be, 24 juni 2018, article in Dutch</ref>\n\n==Athletics career==\nHe was also active as an athlete in [[Track and field|the long jump and sprints]]. He was the Belgian [[long jump]] champion.<ref name=\"onderox\">[http://www.onderox.be/nieuws/539/mon-van-gestel-held-op-het-sportveld-en-in-het-luchtruim Mon Van Gestel: held op het sportveld en in het luchtruim] onderox.be, Jef Aerts, article in Dutch</ref> Due to his versatility he is one of the few Belgian athletes ever to compete in different sports at an international level in the same year.<ref name=\"hln2\"/>\n\n==Later life and death==\nVan Gestel was a [[Fighter pilot]] for the Belgian air force and flight instructor.<ref name=\"motorvliegen\">[https://www.motorvliegen.be/files/fly-in-magazine-2018.pdf Keiheuvel fly-in 2018] motorvliegen.be, 2018, blz. 6</ref><ref>[https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/ggv109kic Vlieginstructeur analyseert dodelijke crash] nieuwsblad.be, 16 augustus 2006</ref> As an instructor he trained around 2000 students.<ref>[https://www.rtv.be/artikels/luchtvaarticoon-en-ex-rode-duivel-mon-van-gestel-90-overleden-a81641 Luchtvaarticoon en ex-Rode Duivel Mon Van Gestel (90) overleden] rtv.be, 18 April 2020</ref> Together with his brother he was also one of the founding members of the Belgian [[Flying club]] Keiheuvel.<ref name=\"hln2\">[https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/balen/gewezen-rode-duivel-en-mede-oprichter-van-vliegclub-keiheuvel-mon-van-gestel-90-overleden-zijn-veelzijdigheid-was-indrukwekkend~adc7b8f5/ Gewezen Rode Duivel en mede-oprichter van vliegclub Keiheuvel Mon Van Gestel (90) overleden: \u201cZijn veelzijdigheid was indrukwekkend] hln.be, Wouter Demuynck, 19 April 2020, article in Dutch</ref><ref name=\"gva\">[https://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20200419_04927290/ex-rode-duivel-en-bezieler-aeroclub-keiheuvel-overleden Ex-Rode Duivel en bezieler Aeroclub Keiheuvel overleden] gva.be, mto, 19 April 2020, article in dutch</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Mol, Belgium|Mol]] on 17 April 2020, aged 90.<ref name=\"gva\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Gestel, Raymond}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgium international footballers]]\n[[Category:K. Lyra players]]\n[[Category:K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Belgian Second Division/Belgian First Division B players]]\n\n{{Belgium-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raymond_Van_Gestel"}
{"title_page": "My Favorite Things (song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = My Favorite Things\n| cover         = \n| cover_size    = \n| alt           = \n| border        = \n| caption       = \n| type          = song\n| artist        = \n| album         = \n| EP            = \n| A-side        = \n| B-side        = \n| written       = \n| published     = 1959 by Williamson Music \n| released      = \n| format        = \n| recorded      = \n| studio        = \n| venue         = \n| genre         = \n| length        =\n| label         = \n| lyricist      = Oscar Hammerstein II\n| composer      = Richard Rodgers\n| producer      = \n| chronology    = \n| prev_title    = <!--for a singles chronology-->\n| prev_year     = \n| next_title    = \n| next_year     = \n| tracks        = <!--see \"Track listing examples\" section for album track listing options-->\n| misc          = <!--for use of {{Extra chronology}}, {{Extra track listing}}, {{Extra album cover}}, {{Audio sample}}, {{External music video}}-->\n}}\n\n\"'''My Favorite Things'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the 1959 [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] musical ''[[The Sound of Music]].''\n\nIn the original [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] production, this song was introduced by [[Mary Martin]] playing [[Maria von Trapp|Maria]] and [[Patricia Neway]] playing Mother Abbess. [[Julie Andrews]], who played Maria in the [[The Sound of Music (film)|1965 film version]] of the musical, had previously sung the song on the 1961 Christmas special for ''[[The Garry Moore Show]]''.\n\n== Background ==\nIn the [[musical theatre|musical]], the lyrics to the song are a reference to things Maria loves, such as \"whiskers on kittens, bright copper kettles and warm woollen mittens\". These are the things she selects to fill her mind with when times are bad.\n\nThe original Broadway musical places the song in the Mother Abbess's office, just before she sends Maria to serve [[Georg Ritter von Trapp|Captain von Trapp]]'s family as governess to his seven children. However, [[Ernest Lehman]], the screenwriter for the film adaptation, repositioned it so that Maria would sing it with the children during the thunderstorm scene in her bedroom, replacing \"[[The Lonely Goatherd]]\", which had originally been sung at this point. Many stage productions also make this change, shifting \"The Lonely Goatherd\" to another scene.\n\nThe first section of the melody has a distinctive property of using only the notes 1, 2, and 5 (tonic, supertonic, and dominant) of the scale. By using the same melody-pattern, Rodgers harmonized it differently in different stanzas, using a series of minor [[Triad (music)|triad]]s one time and major triads the next.\n\nThe song ends with a borrowed line of lyric and notes from Rodgers' earlier composition with [[Lorenz Hart]], \"[[Glad to Be Unhappy]]\", a standard about finding peace in the midst of unrequited love. Using the same two notes for the phrasing of \"so sad\" in the original song, Rodgers brings the gloom of the song to a similar upbeat ending \u2013 \"and then I don't feel so bad.\" Jesus is alife\n\nIn 2004 the movie version of the song finished at No. 64 on [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\n== Other notable versions ==\n\n[[John Coltrane]] played a fourteen-minute version in E minor as the title track of an [[My Favorite Things (John Coltrane album)|album recorded in October 1960 and released in March 1961]]. It became a jazz classic and a signature song for Coltrane in concert, also appearing on ''[[Newport '63]]'' in 1963.<ref name=\"Giddins1998\">{{cite book|author=Gary Giddins|title=Visions of Jazz: The First Century|url=https://archive.org/details/visionsofjazzfir0000gidd_k9c0|url-access=registration|date=October 22, 1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-987953-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/visionsofjazzfir0000gidd_k9c0/page/485 485]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964 [[Jack Jones (singer)|Jack Jones]] became the first of many artists to include the song on a [[Christmas music|Christmas album]], despite its lyrics making no mention of the holiday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/holiday/8078515/my-favorite-things-christmas-sound-of-music|title=Mystery Solved: Here's How 'My Favorite Things' From 'The Sound of Music' Became a Christmas Song|last=Bronson|first=Fred|website=Billboard|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]] released a version in 1969 as a single from their 1968 album, ''[[Christmas Album (Herb Alpert album)|Christmas Album]]''. It reached No. 45 on the [[Billboard 100|''Billboard'' 100]]. [[Lorrie Morgan]]'s version appeared in 1994 and again in 1999 at No. 64 and No. 69, respectively, on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart after she recorded it for her 1993 album, ''[[Merry Christmas from London]]''.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2008|page=287|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[Ariana Grande]] based her song, \"[[7 Rings]]\", around the melody of \"My Favorite Things\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marchershberg/2019/02/07/rodgers-and-hammerstein-top-the-pop-charts/|title=Rodgers and Hammerstein Top the Pop Charts|last=Hershberg|first=Marc|website=Forbes|access-date=March 7, 2019}}</ref> The song topped the charts in fifteen countries.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iro.umontreal.ca/~eckdoug/favorite_things/ Notes, lyrics, mp3s, different versions compared]\n*[http://www.prx.org/pieces/53808-my-favorite-things-at-50/ \"My Favorite Things at 50,\"] public radio documentary on the 50th anniversary of John Coltrane's rendition of \"My Favorite Things.\"\n\n{{Rodgers and Hammerstein}}\n{{The Story of the Trapp Family Singers}}\n\n[[Category:1959 songs]]\n[[Category:List songs]]\n[[Category:American Christmas songs]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in D minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in E-flat minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in E minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in F minor]]\n[[Category:Songs from The Sound of Music]]\n[[Category:Mary Martin songs]]\n[[Category:Julie Andrews songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = My Favorite Things\n| cover         = \n| cover_size    = \n| alt           = \n| border        = \n| caption       = \n| type          = song\n| artist        = \n| album         = \n| EP            = \n| A-side        = \n| B-side        = \n| written       = \n| published     = 1959 by Williamson Music \n| released      = \n| format        = \n| recorded      = \n| studio        = \n| venue         = \n| genre         = \n| length        =\n| label         = \n| lyricist      = Oscar Hammerstein II\n| composer      = Richard Rodgers\n| producer      = \n| chronology    = \n| prev_title    = <!--for a singles chronology-->\n| prev_year     = \n| next_title    = \n| next_year     = \n| tracks        = <!--see \"Track listing examples\" section for album track listing options-->\n| misc          = <!--for use of {{Extra chronology}}, {{Extra track listing}}, {{Extra album cover}}, {{Audio sample}}, {{External music video}}-->\n}}\n\n\"'''My Favorite Things'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the 1959 [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] musical ''[[The Sound of Music]].''\n\nIn the original [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] production, this song was introduced by [[Mary Martin]] playing [[Maria von Trapp|Maria]] and [[Patricia Neway]] playing Mother Abbess. [[Julie Andrews]], who played Maria in the [[The Sound of Music (film)|1965 film version]] of the musical, had previously sung the song on the 1961 Christmas special for ''[[The Garry Moore Show]]''.\n\n== Background ==\nIn the [[musical theatre|musical]], the lyrics to the song are a reference to things Maria loves, such as \"whiskers on kittens, bright copper kettles and warm woollen mittens\". These are the things she selects to fill her mind with when times are bad.\n\nThe original Broadway musical places the song in the Mother Abbess's office, just before she sends Maria to serve [[Georg Ritter von Trapp|Captain von Trapp]]'s family as governess to his seven children. However, [[Ernest Lehman]], the screenwriter for the film adaptation, repositioned it so that Maria would sing it with the children during the thunderstorm scene in her bedroom, replacing \"[[The Lonely Goatherd]]\", which had originally been sung at this point. Many stage productions also make this change, shifting \"The Lonely Goatherd\" to another scene.\n\nThe first section of the melody has a distinctive property of using only the notes 1, 2, and 5 (tonic, supertonic, and dominant) of the scale. By using the same melody-pattern, Rodgers harmonized it differently in different stanzas, using a series of minor [[Triad (music)|triad]]s one time and major triads the next.\n\nThe song ends with a borrowed line of lyric and notes from Rodgers' earlier composition with [[Lorenz Hart]], \"[[Glad to Be Unhappy]]\", a standard about finding peace in the midst of unrequited love. Using the same two notes for the phrasing of \"so sad\" in the original song, Rodgers brings the gloom of the song to a similar upbeat ending \u2013 \"and then I don't feel so bad.\"\n\nIn 2004 the movie version of the song finished at No. 64 on [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\n== Other notable versions ==\n\n[[John Coltrane]] played a fourteen-minute version in E minor as the title track of an [[My Favorite Things (John Coltrane album)|album recorded in October 1960 and released in March 1961]]. It became a jazz classic and a signature song for Coltrane in concert, also appearing on ''[[Newport '63]]'' in 1963.<ref name=\"Giddins1998\">{{cite book|author=Gary Giddins|title=Visions of Jazz: The First Century|url=https://archive.org/details/visionsofjazzfir0000gidd_k9c0|url-access=registration|date=October 22, 1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-987953-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/visionsofjazzfir0000gidd_k9c0/page/485 485]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964 [[Jack Jones (singer)|Jack Jones]] became the first of many artists to include the song on a [[Christmas music|Christmas album]], despite its lyrics making no mention of the holiday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/holiday/8078515/my-favorite-things-christmas-sound-of-music|title=Mystery Solved: Here's How 'My Favorite Things' From 'The Sound of Music' Became a Christmas Song|last=Bronson|first=Fred|website=Billboard|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]] released a version in 1969 as a single from their 1968 album, ''[[Christmas Album (Herb Alpert album)|Christmas Album]]''. It reached No. 45 on the [[Billboard 100|''Billboard'' 100]]. [[Lorrie Morgan]]'s version appeared in 1994 and again in 1999 at No. 64 and No. 69, respectively, on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart after she recorded it for her 1993 album, ''[[Merry Christmas from London]]''.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2008|page=287|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[Ariana Grande]] based her song, \"[[7 Rings]]\", around the melody of \"My Favorite Things\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marchershberg/2019/02/07/rodgers-and-hammerstein-top-the-pop-charts/|title=Rodgers and Hammerstein Top the Pop Charts|last=Hershberg|first=Marc|website=Forbes|access-date=March 7, 2019}}</ref> The song topped the charts in fifteen countries.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iro.umontreal.ca/~eckdoug/favorite_things/ Notes, lyrics, mp3s, different versions compared]\n*[http://www.prx.org/pieces/53808-my-favorite-things-at-50/ \"My Favorite Things at 50,\"] public radio documentary on the 50th anniversary of John Coltrane's rendition of \"My Favorite Things.\"\n\n{{Rodgers and Hammerstein}}\n{{The Story of the Trapp Family Singers}}\n\n[[Category:1959 songs]]\n[[Category:List songs]]\n[[Category:American Christmas songs]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in D minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in E-flat minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in E minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in F minor]]\n[[Category:Songs from The Sound of Music]]\n[[Category:Mary Martin songs]]\n[[Category:Julie Andrews songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n", "name_user": "80.57.212.244", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBackground)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Favorite_Things_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Penny O'Donnell", "text_new": "\n\n'''Dr Penny O'Donnell''' is a bilingual radio journalist, author and media scholar, best known for her research into global journalism, comparative media, and the effects of digital transformation on job losses among Australian journalists. \n\n== Biography ==\nO'Donnell received a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) from [[University of Melbourne]] in 1981, a Masters of Social Communication from the [[Iberoamericana University]], Mexico, in 1993 and her PhD from [[University of Technology Sydney|University of Technology,]] Sydney in 2006. A former journalist for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC), she began lecturing at the School of Journalism at the [[Central American University (Managua)|Central American University]] in Managua, Nicaragua, before returning to Australia to teach at [[University of Technology Sydney]], receiving a Team Teaching Award for creating new dialogues about race, power, subjectivity, and intercultural communication<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/penny-odonnell-12067|title=Penny O'Donnell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. She joined [[University of Sydney]] as Senior Lecturer in International Media and Journalism in 2008, where she is also Degree Director for the Master of Media Practice.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydney.edu.au/arts/about/our-people/academic-staff/staff-profile.html|title=Staff Profile|website=The University of Sydney|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> O'Donnell serves on the Editorial Board of ''[[Journalism & Mass Communication Educator|Journalism and Mass Communication Educator]]'' and the Advisory Board of ''Global Media Journal \u2014 Australian edition.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hca.westernsydney.edu.au/gmjau/?page_id=45|title=Global Media Journal: Australian Edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nO'Donnell's interest in Central American culture and media started when she was sent by the ABC to cover the 1986 International Peace March. She returned a year later to Nicaragua for three years and published two books about the experience. The first, ''[https://www.amazon.com/Death-dreams-dancing-Nicaragua-ODonnell/dp/0733301142 Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua]'', is a travel memoir which also provides a case study to demonstrate the importance of radio education for impoverished communities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arnove|first=Robert|title=Comparative Education: The Dialectic of the Global and the Local|publisher=Rowan & Littlefield|year=2013|isbn=978-1442217768|location=|pages=216}}</ref> Her second book, ''Dar la palabra al pueblo: La ense\u00f1anza-aprendizaje de la comunicaci\u00f3n en Nicaragua durante la Revoluci\u00f3n Popular Sandinista (Giving the word to the people: the teaching-learning of communication in Nicaragua during the Sandinista Popular Revolution),'' was published by the Iberoamericana Universidad, Mexico, and is cited in the ''Encyclopedia of Social Movement Media''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Downing|first=John|url=http://sk.sagepub.com/reference/socialmovement|title=Encyclopedia of Social Movement Media|date=2011|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=Thousand Oaks, California|pages=502|doi=10.4135/9781412979313}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 1995, after returning to Australia, she co-authored the book ''[https://books.google.com.au/books/about/Australians_Against_Racism.html?id=X5sPAQAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia].'' In 2012 she co-authored a monograph, ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century,'' about job losses among Australian journalists caused by the expansion of digital media. \n\nO'Donnell has co-presented submissions to Australian government inquiries into the media and journalism, including [[Raymond Finkelstein|Hon R Finklestein']]<nowiki/>s 2012 inquiry into media regulation, the 2017 Future of Public Interest Journalism Inquiry, and in 2018 the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers.\n\nO'Donnell is a member of:\n\n*[[International Communication Association]] (ICA)\n*[https://iamcr.org/ International Association for Media and Communication Research] (IAMCR)\n*[https://jeraa.org.au/ Journalism Education and Research Association of Australia] (JERAA)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Australian Research Council ===\nO'Donnell was funded by the [[Australian Research Council]] (ARC) in 2009 as Lead Chief Investigator into the future of newspapers, along with [https://research.unsw.edu.au/people/associate-professor-david-mcknight Associate Professor David McKnight], from [[University of New South Wales]]. In 2012 she became Chief Investigator on the ARC-funded New Beats Project, which involved seven journalism academics from five Australian universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/the-new-beats-team/|title=The New Beats team|date=2013-11-27|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The study focused on the mass redundancies of 3000 journalists who lost their jobs in Australia between 2012 and 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.org.au/articles/exiting-journalists-marching-new-beat-survey-finds|title=Exiting journalists marching to a new beat, survey finds|website=The Citizen|language=en-au|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/new-research-reveals-how-australian-journalists-are-faring-four-years-after-redundancy-107520|title=New research reveals how Australian journalists are faring four years after redundancy|last=Dodd|first=Andrew|last2=Zion|first2=Lawrie|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ricketson|first3=Matthew|last4=Sherwood|first4=Merryn|last5=Winarnita|first5=Monika|last6=O'Donnell|first6=Penny|last7=Marjoribanks|first7=Timothy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au|title=Study follows new beats in journalism|last=Sinclair|first=Lara|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>. A second round of ARC funding allowed the research to expand internationally and New Beats II included collaborators such as [[:nl:Mark_Deuze|Professor Mark Deuze]] in the Netherlands, as well as academics in America, Canada, Indonesia and South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/|title=New Beats|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\nO'Donnell, Penny (1991) ''Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua,'' ABC Enterprises, Crows Nest, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, Penelope (1995) ''Dar la palabra al pueblo: La ense\u00f1anza-aprendizaje de la comunicaci\u00f3n en Nicaragua durante la Revoluci\u00f3n Popular Sandinista'', Universidad Iberoamericana, Mexico.\n\nO'Donnell, Penny & Simons, Lynette (1995) ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia,'' Pluto Press, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, P., McKnight, D., Este, J. (2012). ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century''. Sydney, Australia: Walkley Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/meaa/docs/2012_journalism_speed_of_bytes|title=Journalism at the speed of bytes|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Submissions ===\n\n*O'Donnell, P., Zion, L., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2018), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers from the New Beats Project, Submission 140''.\n* Zion, L., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., O'Donnell, P., Ricketson, M., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2017), ''New Beats Project Submission to the Senate Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 37''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Future_of_Public_Interest_Journalism/PublicInterestJournalism/Submissions|title=Submissions|last=|first=|date=|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Dwyer, T., Martin, F., O'Donnell, P. (2017), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 44. June 2017''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n== Selected scholarly publications ==\n\n* O'Donnell, P., Zion, L. (2019). Precarity in Media Work. In Mark Deuze, Mirjam Prenger (Eds.), ''Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions'', (pp. 223\u2013234). Amsterdam: Amsterdam University Press<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|title=Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions|date=2019-01-14|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|year=|isbn=978-90-485-4015-0|editor-last=Deuze|editor-first=Mark|location=|pages=|doi=10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|editor-last2=Prenger|editor-first2=Mirjam}}</ref>\n* Cohen, N., Hunter, A., O'Donnell, P. (2019). Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism. ''Journalism Practice'', 13(7), (pp. 817\u2013833)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Nicole S.|last2=Hunter|first2=Andrea|last3=O\u2019Donnell|first3=Penny|date=2019-08-09|title=Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|journal=Journalism Practice|volume=13|issue=7|pages=817\u2013833|doi=10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|issn=1751-2786}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2018). Australian Journalists at Work. In Eric Freedman, Robyn S. Goodman, Elanie Steyn (Eds.), ''Critical Perspectives on Journalistic Beliefs and Actions: Global Experiences'', (pp. 24\u201334). New York: Routledge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/|title=Australian Journalists at Work : Their Views on Employment, Unionization, and Professional Identity|last=O\u2019Donnell|first=Penny|date=2018-05-11|website=Critical Perspectives on Journalistic Beliefs and Actions|language=en|doi=10.4324/9781315161099-3|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Zion, L., Sherwood, M., O'Donnell, P., Marjoribanks, T., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Winarnita, M. (2018). ''New Beats Report: Mass redundancies and career change in Australian journalism'', (pp. 1\u201328). Melbourne, Australia: The New Beats Project\n* Sherwood, M., O'Donnell, P. (2018). Once a Journalist, Always a Journalist? Industry Restructure, Job Loss and Professional Identity. ''Journalism Studies'', 19(7), 1021\u20131038<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherwood|first=Merryn|last2=O\u2019Donnell|first2=Penny|date=2018-05-19|title=Once a Journalist, Always a Journalist?|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/1461670X.2016.1249007|journal=Journalism Studies|volume=19|issue=7|pages=1021\u20131038|doi=10.1080/1461670X.2016.1249007|issn=1461-670X}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2017). Journalism Education in Australia: Educating Journalists for Convergent, Cosmopolitan, and Uncertain News Environments.  In Robyn S. Goodman, Elanie Steyn (Eds.), ''Global Journalism Education in the 21st Century: Challenges and Innovations'', (pp. 17\u201340). Austin: The University of Texas at Austin\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\nPersonal Blog: https://pennyodonnell.com/\n\nNew Beats Project: http://www.newbeatsblog.com/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:O'Donnell, Penny}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian travel writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women writers]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Dr Penny O'Donnell''' is a bilingual radio journalist, author and media scholar, best known for her research into global journalism, comparative media, and the effects of digital transformation on job losses among Australian journalists. \n\n== Biography ==\nO'Donnell received a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) from [[University of Melbourne]] in 1981, a Masters of Social Communication from the [[Iberoamericana University]], Mexico, in 1993 and her PhD from [[University of Technology Sydney|University of Technology,]] Sydney in 2006. A former journalist for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC), she began lecturing at the School of Journalism at the [[Central American University (Managua)|Central American University]] in Managua, Nicaragua, before returning to Australia to teach at [[University of Technology Sydney]], receiving a Team Teaching Award for creating new dialogues about race, power, subjectivity, and intercultural communication<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/penny-odonnell-12067|title=Penny O'Donnell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. She joined [[University of Sydney]] as Senior Lecturer in International Media and Journalism in 2008, where she is also Degree Director for the Master of Media Practice.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydney.edu.au/arts/about/our-people/academic-staff/staff-profile.html|title=Staff Profile|website=The University of Sydney|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> O'Donnell serves on the Editorial Board of ''[[Journalism & Mass Communication Educator|Journalism and Mass Communication Educator]]'' and the Advisory Board of ''Global Media Journal \u2014 Australian edition.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hca.westernsydney.edu.au/gmjau/?page_id=45|title=Global Media Journal: Australian Edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nO'Donnell's interest in Central American culture and media started when she was sent by the ABC to cover the 1986 International Peace March. She returned a year later to Nicaragua for three years and published two books about the experience. The first, ''[https://www.amazon.com/Death-dreams-dancing-Nicaragua-ODonnell/dp/0733301142 Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua]'', is a travel memoir which also provides a case study to demonstrate the importance of radio education for impoverished communities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arnove|first=Robert|title=Comparative Education: The Dialectic of the Global and the Local|publisher=Rowan & Littlefield|year=2013|isbn=978-1442217768|location=|pages=216}}</ref> Her second book, ''Dar la palabra al pueblo: La ense\u00f1anza-aprendizaje de la comunicaci\u00f3n en Nicaragua durante la Revoluci\u00f3n Popular Sandinista (Giving the word to the people: the teaching-learning of communication in Nicaragua during the Sandinista Popular Revolution),'' was published by the Iberoamericana Universidad, Mexico, and is cited in the ''Encyclopedia of Social Movement Media''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Downing|first=John|url=http://sk.sagepub.com/reference/socialmovement|title=Encyclopedia of Social Movement Media|date=2011|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=Thousand Oaks, California|pages=502|doi=10.4135/9781412979313}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 1995, after returning to Australia, she co-authored the book ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia.'' In 2012 she co-authored a monograph, ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century,'' about job losses among Australian journalists caused by the expansion of digital media. \n\nO'Donnell has co-presented submissions to Australian government inquiries into the media and journalism, including [[Raymond Finkelstein|Hon R Finklestein']]<nowiki/>s 2012 inquiry into media regulation, the 2017 Future of Public Interest Journalism Inquiry, and in 2018 the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers.\n\nO'Donnell is a member of:\n\n*[[International Communication Association]] (ICA)\n*[https://iamcr.org/ International Association for Media and Communication Research] (IAMCR)\n*[https://jeraa.org.au/ Journalism Education and Research Association of Australia] (JERAA)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Australian Research Council ===\nO'Donnell was funded by the [[Australian Research Council]] (ARC) in 2009 as Lead Chief Investigator into the future of newspapers, along with [https://research.unsw.edu.au/people/associate-professor-david-mcknight Associate Professor David McKnight], from [[University of New South Wales]]. In 2012 she became Chief Investigator on the ARC-funded New Beats Project, which involved seven journalism academics from five Australian universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/the-new-beats-team/|title=The New Beats team|date=2013-11-27|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The study focused on the mass redundancies of 3000 journalists who lost their jobs in Australia between 2012 and 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.org.au/articles/exiting-journalists-marching-new-beat-survey-finds|title=Exiting journalists marching to a new beat, survey finds|website=The Citizen|language=en-au|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/new-research-reveals-how-australian-journalists-are-faring-four-years-after-redundancy-107520|title=New research reveals how Australian journalists are faring four years after redundancy|last=Dodd|first=Andrew|last2=Zion|first2=Lawrie|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ricketson|first3=Matthew|last4=Sherwood|first4=Merryn|last5=Winarnita|first5=Monika|last6=O'Donnell|first6=Penny|last7=Marjoribanks|first7=Timothy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au|title=Study follows new beats in journalism|last=Sinclair|first=Lara|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>. A second round of ARC funding allowed the research to expand internationally and New Beats II included collaborators such as [[:nl:Mark_Deuze|Professor Mark Deuze]] in the Netherlands, as well as academics in America, Canada, Indonesia and South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/|title=New Beats|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\nO'Donnell, Penny (1991) ''Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua,'' ABC Enterprises, Crows Nest, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, Penelope (1995) ''Dar la palabra al pueblo: La ense\u00f1anza-aprendizaje de la comunicaci\u00f3n en Nicaragua durante la Revoluci\u00f3n Popular Sandinista'', Universidad Iberoamericana, Mexico.\n\nO'Donnell, Penny & Simons, Lynette (1995) ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia,'' Pluto Press, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, P., McKnight, D., Este, J. (2012). ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century''. Sydney, Australia: Walkley Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/meaa/docs/2012_journalism_speed_of_bytes|title=Journalism at the speed of bytes|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Submissions ===\n\n*O'Donnell, P., Zion, L., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2018), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers from the New Beats Project, Submission 140''.\n* Zion, L., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., O'Donnell, P., Ricketson, M., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2017), ''New Beats Project Submission to the Senate Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 37''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Future_of_Public_Interest_Journalism/PublicInterestJournalism/Submissions|title=Submissions|last=|first=|date=|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Dwyer, T., Martin, F., O'Donnell, P. (2017), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 44. June 2017''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n== Selected scholarly publications ==\n\n* O'Donnell, P., Zion, L. (2019). Precarity in Media Work. In Mark Deuze, Mirjam Prenger (Eds.), ''Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions'', (pp. 223\u2013234). Amsterdam: Amsterdam University Press<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|title=Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions|date=2019-01-14|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|year=|isbn=978-90-485-4015-0|editor-last=Deuze|editor-first=Mark|location=|pages=|doi=10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|editor-last2=Prenger|editor-first2=Mirjam}}</ref>\n* Cohen, N., Hunter, A., O'Donnell, P. (2019). Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism. ''Journalism Practice'', 13(7), (pp. 817\u2013833)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Nicole S.|last2=Hunter|first2=Andrea|last3=O\u2019Donnell|first3=Penny|date=2019-08-09|title=Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|journal=Journalism Practice|volume=13|issue=7|pages=817\u2013833|doi=10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|issn=1751-2786}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2018). Australian Journalists at Work. In Eric Freedman, Robyn S. Goodman, Elanie Steyn (Eds.), ''Critical Perspectives on Journalistic Beliefs and Actions: Global Experiences'', (pp. 24\u201334). New York: Routledge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/|title=Australian Journalists at Work : Their Views on Employment, Unionization, and Professional Identity|last=O\u2019Donnell|first=Penny|date=2018-05-11|website=Critical Perspectives on Journalistic Beliefs and Actions|language=en|doi=10.4324/9781315161099-3|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Zion, L., Sherwood, M., O'Donnell, P., Marjoribanks, T., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Winarnita, M. (2018). ''New Beats Report: Mass redundancies and career change in Australian journalism'', (pp. 1\u201328). Melbourne, Australia: The New Beats Project\n* Sherwood, M., O'Donnell, P. (2018). Once a Journalist, Always a Journalist? Industry Restructure, Job Loss and Professional Identity. ''Journalism Studies'', 19(7), 1021\u20131038<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherwood|first=Merryn|last2=O\u2019Donnell|first2=Penny|date=2018-05-19|title=Once a Journalist, Always a Journalist?|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/1461670X.2016.1249007|journal=Journalism Studies|volume=19|issue=7|pages=1021\u20131038|doi=10.1080/1461670X.2016.1249007|issn=1461-670X}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2017). Journalism Education in Australia: Educating Journalists for Convergent, Cosmopolitan, and Uncertain News Environments.  In Robyn S. Goodman, Elanie Steyn (Eds.), ''Global Journalism Education in the 21st Century: Challenges and Innovations'', (pp. 17\u201340). Austin: The University of Texas at Austin\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\nPersonal Blog: https://pennyodonnell.com/\n\nNew Beats Project: http://www.newbeatsblog.com/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:O'Donnell, Penny}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian travel writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Fransplace", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penny_O%27Donnell"}
{"title_page": "The Girl of the Golden West (1915 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1915 film}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl of the Golden West\n| image          = The Girl of the Golden West.jpg\n| caption        = Advertisement (1918)\n| director       = [[Cecil B. DeMille]]\n| producer       = Cecil B. DeMille\n| writer         = Cecil B. DeMille\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[The Girl of the Golden West (play)|The Girl of the Golden West]]''|[[David Belasco]]}}\n| starring       = [[Mabel Van Buren]]\n| cinematography = Alvin Wyckoff\n| editing        = Cecil B. DeMille<br />W. Donn Hayes\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1915|1|4}}\n| runtime        = 50 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n'''''The Girl of the Golden West''''' is a surviving 1915 American [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[silent film|silent]] [[black-and-white film]] directed by [[Cecil B. DeMille]]. It was based on the 1905 play ''[[The Girl of the Golden West (play)|The Girl of the Golden West]]'' by [[David Belasco]]. Prints of the film survive in the [[Library of Congress]] film archive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/G/GirlOfTheGoldenWest1915.html|title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''The Girl of the Golden West''|accessdate=October 20, 2009|publisher=silentera.com}}</ref> It was the first of four film adaptations that have been made of the play.\n\n==Plot==\nA hard-bitten saloon girl falls for a dashing outlaw, and tries to keep the local sheriff from catching him and sending him to prison. \n\n==Cast==\n{{Right|[[File:Fanciulla del West film poster by Spellani.jpg|thumb|Poster for the Italian release]]}}\n* [[Mabel Van Buren]] as The Girl\n* [[Theodore Roberts]] as Jack Rance\n* [[House Peters Sr.]] as Ramerrez\n* [[Anita King]] as Wowkle\n* [[Sydney Deane]] as Sidney Duck\n* [[William Elmer]] as Ashby (credited as Billy Elmer)\n* [[Jeanie MacPherson]] as Nina (credited as Jeane McPherson)\n* [[Raymond Hatton]] as Castro\n* Richard L'Estrange as Senor Slim (credited as Dick Le Strange)\n* Tex Driscoll as Nick, The Bartender\n* [[Artie Ortego]] as Antonio (credited as Arthur Ortego)\n* John Oretgo as Stagecoach Driver\n* James Griswold as Guard\n* [[Edwin Harley]] as Old Minstrel\n\n==Preservation status==\nPrints survive at [[George Eastman Museum]], the [[Library of Congress]], {{ill|Cineteca del Friuli|it}} ([[Gemona del Friuli|Gemona]]), [[Academy Film Archive]] (Beverly Hills).<ref>[https://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.1495/default.html The Library of Congress Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: ''The Girl of the Golden West'']</ref><ref>''Catalog of Holdings The American Film Institute Collection and The United Artists Collection at The Library of Congress'', p. 68 c.1978 by the American Film Institute</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|The Girl of the Golden West (1915 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0005393|The Girl of the Golden West}}\n\n{{Cecil B. DeMille}}\n{{The Girl of the Golden West}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl Of The Golden West, The}}\n[[Category:1915 films]]\n[[Category:1915 Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Cecil B. DeMille]]\n{{1910s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1915 film}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl of the Golden West\n| image          = The Girl of the Golden West.jpg\n| caption        = Advertisement (1918)\n| director       = [[Cecil B. DeMille]]\n| producer       = Cecil B. DeMille\n| writer         = Cecil B. DeMille\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[The Girl of the Golden West (play)|The Girl of the Golden West]]''|[[David Belasco]]}}\n| starring       = [[Mabel Van Buren]]\n| cinematography = Alvin Wyckoff\n| editing        = Cecil B. DeMille<br />W. Donn Hayes\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1915|1|4}}\n| runtime        = 50 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n'''''The Girl of the Golden West''''' is a surviving 1915 American [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[silent film|silent]] [[black-and-white film]] directed by [[Cecil B. DeMille]]. It was based on the 1905 play ''[[The Girl of the Golden West (play)|The Girl of the Golden West]]'' by [[David Belasco]]. Prints of the film survive in the [[Library of Congress]] film archive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/G/GirlOfTheGoldenWest1915.html|title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''The Girl of the Golden West''|accessdate=October 20, 2009|publisher=silentera.com}}</ref> It was the first of four film adaptations that have been made of the play.\n\n==Plot==\nA hard-bitten saloon girl falls for a dashing outlaw, and tries to keep the local sheriff from catching him and sending him to prison. \n\n==Cast==\n{{Right|[[File:Fanciulla del West film poster by Spellani.jpg|thumb|Poster for the Italian release]]}}\n* [[Mabel Van Buren]] as The Girl\n* [[Theodore Roberts]] as Jack Rance\n* [[House Peters Sr.]] as Ramerrez\n* [[Anita King]] as Wowkle\n* [[Sydney Deane]] as Sidney Duck\n* [[William Elmer]] as Ashby (credited as Billy Elmer)\n* [[Jeanie MacPherson]] as Nina (credited as Jeane McPherson)\n* [[Raymond Hatton]] as Castro\n* Richard L'Estrange as Senor Slim (credited as Dick Le Strange)\n* Tex Driscoll as Nick, The Bartender\n* [[Artie Ortego]] as Antonio (credited as Arthur Ortego)\n* John Oretgo as Stagecoach Driver\n* James Griswold as Guard\n* [[Edwin Harley]] as Old Minstrel\n\n==Preservation status==\nPrints survive at [[George Eastman Museum]], the [[Library of Congress]], {{ill|Cineteca del Friuli|it}} ([[Gemona del Friuli|Gemona]]), [[Academy Film Archive]] (Beverly Hills).<ref>[https://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.1495/default.html The Library of Congress Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: ''The Girl of the Golden West'']</ref><ref>''Catalog of Holdings The American Film Institute Collection and The United Artists Collection at The Library of Congress'', p. 68 c.1978 by the American Film Institute</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|The Girl of the Golden West (1915 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0005393|The Girl of the Golden West}}\n\n{{Cecil B. DeMille}}\n{{The Girl of the Golden West}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl Of The Golden West, The}}\n[[Category:1915 films]]\n[[Category:1915 Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Cecil B. DeMille]]\n{{1910s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Girl_of_the_Golden_West_(1915_film)"}
{"title_page": "Vangelis Pavlidis", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Vangelis Pavlidis\n| fullname            = Evangelos Pavlidis<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2015/teams/player=250078012/index.html|title=Vangelis Pavlidis|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|11|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Thessaloniki]], Greece\n| height              = 1.86 m\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|Centre forward]]\n| currentclub         = [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]]\n| clubnumber          = 10\n| youthyears1         = 2004\u20132014\n| youthclubs1         = Bebides 2000 FA Saloniki\n| youthyears2         = 2015\u20132017\n| youthclubs2         = [[VfL Bochum]]\n| years1              = 2016\u20132019\n| clubs1              = [[VfL Bochum]]\n| caps1               = 4\n| goals1              = 0\n| years2              = 2017\u20132019\n| clubs2              = \u2192 [[Borussia Dortmund II]] (loan)\n| caps2               = 32\n| goals2              = 7\n| years3              = 2019\n| clubs3              = \u2192 [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] (loan)\n| caps3               = 14\n| goals3              = 5\n| years4              = 2019\u2013\n| clubs4              = [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]]\n| caps4               = 25\n| goals4              = 11\n| nationalyears1      = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam1       = [[Greece national under-17 football team|Greece U17]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 13\n| nationalgoals1      = 4\n| nationalyears2      = 2015\u20132017\n| nationalteam2       = [[Greece national under-19 football team|Greece U19]]\n| nationalcaps2       = 11\n| nationalgoals2      = 3\n| nationalyears3      = 2018\n| nationalteam3       = [[Greece national under-20 football team|Greece U20]]\n| nationalcaps3       = 2\n| nationalgoals3      = 0\n| nationalyears4      = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam4       = [[Greece national under-21 football team|Greece U21]]\n| nationalcaps4       = 2\n| nationalgoals4      = 3\n| nationalteam5       = [[Greece national football team|Greece]]\n| nationalcaps5       = 5\n| nationalgoals5      = 1\n| nationalyears5      = 2019\u2013\n| club-update         = 19:18, 8 March 2020 (UTC).\n| nationalteam-update = 13:30, 19 November 2019 (UTC).\n}}\n'''Vangelis Pavlidis''' ({{lang-el|\u0392\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03ad\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 21 November 1998) is a Greek professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]] for Dutch club [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] and the [[Greece national football team|Greece national team]].<ref name=\"kicker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/vereine/2-bundesliga/2017-18/vfl-bochum-8/89860/spieler_evangelos-pavlidis.html|language=German|title=Vangelis Pavlidis|publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]]|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref><ref name = \"WF\">{{Worldfootball.net|evangelos-pavlidis}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===VfL Bochum===\nOn 9 April 2016, Pavlidis signed a professional contract until the summer of 2019. Pavlidis is in the Bochum team for one and half years and has redeemed his stunning appearances in the [[Under 19 Bundesliga|Bundesliga U19]] competitive league (45 matches - 20 goals - 13 assists) and his excellent presence with the first Bochum team in which he regularly participated in the training sessions, as well as in official friendly games. Pavlidis was voted, according to [[FIFA]], as one of the 15 greatest talents in the finals of the previous [[UEFA European Under-17 Championship|European U17 Championship]] in Bulgaria. The Westphalian team is betting a lot to the young striker since the [[2016\u201317 2. Bundesliga|2016\u201317 season]], so it hastened to bind him with a new contract until 2019, as German, English and Italian teams have been very interested in the past few years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/EllinesExoterikou/epaggelmatias-sta-17-o-paylidhs-sth-mpoxoym.3999927.html |language=Greek |title=\u0395\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 17 \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u039c\u03c0\u03cc\u03c7\u03bf\u03c5\u03bc |publisher=www.sport24.gr|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 May 2016, he made his debut with the club as a substitute in a [[2. Bundesliga]] 4\u20132 away win against [[1. FC Heidenheim]].\n\n====Loan to Borussia Dortmund II====\nOn 26 January 2018, Pavlidis joined [[Borussia Dortmund II]] on loan for the second half of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bochum holt Serra und gibt Pavlidis an den BVB ab|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/startseite/715947/artikel_bochum-holt-serra-und-gibt-pavlidis-an-den-bvb-ab.html|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]]|date=26 January 2018|language=German}}</ref> On 22 June 2018, Pavlidis loan spell was extended until summer 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|title=VfL verl\u00e4ngert mit Pavlidis und leiht ihn erneut aus|language=German|date=22 June 2018|publisher=[[VfL Bochum]]|url=https://www.vfl-bochum.de/news/uebersicht/profis/vfl-verlaengert-mit-pavlidis-und-leiht-ihn-erneut-aus/}}</ref> \n\n====Loan to Willem II====\nOn 17 January 2019, [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] confirmed the signing of young Greek international on loan from Bochum until the end of the [[2018-19 Eredivisie|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Willem II sign Greek duo|language=English |date=17 January 2019 |publisher=www.football-oranje.com |url=http://www.football-oranje.com/willem-ii-sign-greek-duo/}}</ref> On 23 January 2019, he scored his first goal with the club after [[Marios Vrousai]]'s assist in a 3\u20132 away [[KNVB Beker]] win against [[FC Twente]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u0392\u03af\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc: \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf \u03b3\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7, \u03b4\u03c5\u03bf \u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03c3\u03c4 \u03bf \u0392\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03ac\u03b9 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c1\u03cc\u03ba\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b7\u03bc\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u039a\u03c5\u03c0\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 |date=23 January 2019 |publisher=www.sport24.gr |url=https://www.sport24.gr/football/EllinesExoterikou/vilem-prwto-gkol-gia-paylidh-dyo-asist-o-vroysai-kai-prokrish-ston-hmiteliko-toy-kypelloy.5421468.html}}</ref>\nOn 16 February 2019, he scored his first goal in [[Eredivisie]], with a right footed shot from very close range to the bottom right corner in a 3\u20132 away loss against [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Vitesse - Willem II 3:2|date=16 February 2019 |publisher=www.foxsports.it |url=https://www.foxsports.it/calcio/2019-02-16/vit-wil-risultato/}}</ref>\n\nPavlidis only moved to Willem II as a loanee from German side [[VfL Bochum]] in January, but he's already managed to make a solid impression in the Eredivisie, popping up with two goals and three assists in seven league games. He's also registered one goal and one assist in the Dutch Cup. On 3 March 2019, Pavlidis struck gold netting his club's second goal in a 2\u20134 loss to [[SC Heerenveen]] on the road.<ref>{{Cite web|title=SC Heerenveen - Willem II 4:2|date=3 March 2019 |publisher=www.fcupdate.nl |url=https://www.fcupdate.nl/voetbaluitslagen/290555/eredivisie-sc-heerenveen-willem-ii/}}</ref>\n\n===Willem II===\nOn 29 April 2019, Pavlidis will play his football with Willem II until 2022 after signing a permanent deal with the club. The 20-year-old striker, who was on the books at Bochum in Germany, made a loan move to the Eredivisie for Willem II in January and since then, has had a tremendous spell with the Dutch club. Across all competitions, the striker has scored four goals and registered five assists in 14 appearances. As a result, Willem II decided to make Pavlidis\u2019 move a permanent one and the youngster signed a contract with the Dutch club through 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u0391\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7 \u03b7 \u0392\u03af\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc |date=29 April 2019 |publisher=www.enwsi.gr |url=https://www.enwsi.gr/paraskinia/gossip/agorase-paylidi-i-vilem/}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2018, in the opening game of the [[2019\u201320 Eredivisie]] Pavlidis scored twice as Willem II defeated [[PEC Zwolle]] 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u0394\u03cd\u03bf \u03b3\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2, \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u2026 \u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03af \u03b7 \u0392\u03af\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc |date=2 August 2019 |publisher=www.to10.gr |url=https://www.to10.gr/podosfero/europe/694363/dyo-gkol-o-pavlidis-dexi-vilem-vid/}}</ref> Two weeks later, he converted a penalty after he himself had been fouled, and scored a second with a header, as Willem II beat [[Fortuna Sittard]] 3\u20132 away from home.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Willem II trekt aan langste eind in waterballet tegen Fortuna Sittard |date=18 August 2019 |publisher=www.voetbalzone.nl |url=https://www.voetbalzone.nl/doc.asp?uid=357467 |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref> On 15 September, Pavlidis scored in a 4\u20131 away loss against [[Heracles Almelo]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Heracles Almelo too strong for Willem II |date=15 September 2019 |publisher=www.football-oranje.com |url=https://www.football-oranje.com/heracles-almelo-too-strong-for-willem-ii/ |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> A week later he scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 home win game against [[VVV-Venlo]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Pavlidis leads Willem II to win over VVV |date=21 September 2019 |publisher=www.football-oranje.com |url=https://www.football-oranje.com/pavlidis-leads-willem-ii-to-win-over-vvv/ |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> On 23 November 2019, he scored a brace after assisted by [[Mats K\u00f6hlert]] and [[Marios Vrousai]] respectively helping his club to acquire a vital away 3\u20133 draw against [[ADO Den Haag]]. These were Pavlidis\u2019 first goals since he scored for Greece against Bosnia in [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] in October.<ref>{{Cite web|title=ADO Den Haag vs Willem II 3-3 |date=23 November 2019 |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/den-haag-vs-willem-ii/408861 |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref> On 13 December 2019, Pavlidis opened the score, as Willem II defeated [[SC Heerenveen]] 2\u20131 on the road in the Eredivisie.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Willem II sluit feestweek af met uitzege bij Heerenveen |date=13 December 2019 |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2314643-willem-ii-sluit-feestweek-af-met-uitzege-bij-heerenveen.html |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2020, Pavlidis notched his first goal of 2020 with Willem II, netting the second marker for his team in an important 3\u20131 triumph at [[AZ Alkmaar]]. With 12 minutes remaining, Pavlidis neatly collected the ball inside the penalty area, took aim and dinked his shot over the onrushing goalkeeper to give Willem II the lead.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Willem II in the final phase 1-3 in Alkmaar against AZ |date=18 January 2020 |url=https://www.tellerreport.com/sports/2020-01-18---willem-ii-in-the-final-phase-1-3-in-alkmaar-against-az-.Byf212g-WU.html |accessdate=19 January 2020}}</ref> On 22 January 2020, in the [[KNVB Cup]], the international striker hit the target as Willem II eventually ended up losing to [[SC Heerenveen]]. On 28 February 2020, he scored with a right footed shot from the centre of the box to the bottom right corner, after an assist from [[G\u00f6rkem Saglam]] in a 3\u20131 home win game against [[FC Groningen]]. Midway through the second half, the 21-year-old forward then contributed with an assist for his team\u2019s third, as his low feed across the box was tapped home by [[Mats Kohlert]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Willem II heeft in eigen huis weinig problemen met FC Groningen |date=28 February 2020 |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2325049-willem-ii-heeft-in-eigen-huis-weinig-problemen-met-fc-groningen.html |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 29 August 2019, Pavlidis was called up to the [[Greece national football team|Greek senior team]] by coach [[John van 't Schip]] for the forthcoming [[Euro 2020]] qualifiers against [[Finland national football team|Finland]] and [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=PAVLIDIS AND VROUSAI BOTH INCLUDED IN GREECE SQUAD |date=29 September 2019 |publisher=www.agonasport.com |url=https://www.agonasport.com/agonasport-allnews/pavlidis-and-vrousai-included-in-greece-squad |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|8 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[VfL Bochum]]||[[2015\u201316 2. Bundesliga|2015\u201316]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[2. Bundesliga]]||1||0||0||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 2. Bundesliga|2016\u201317]]||3||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 2. Bundesliga|2017\u201318]]||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!4!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!4!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Borussia Dortmund II]]||[[2017\u201318 Regionalliga|2017\u201318]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Regionalliga West]]||17||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||17||5\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Regionalliga|2018\u201319]]||15||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||15||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!32!!7!!0!!0!!0!!0!!32!!7\